</td>
<td>
<BR>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><P><I>&quot;The idea came to mind as a complete thought, 
as clearly as the first order to go to New York. And 
along with it came into my mind the picture of a house 
where these new kids would come. A really nice house, 
all their own, where they would be 
welcomedwelcomed and loved. They could live in their house any time 
they wanted to.  The door would always be open; 
there would always be lots and lots of beds, and clothes 
to wear, and a great big kitchen.&quot;
</FONT>
</font>
<P>
<H5> Reverend David Wilkerson<BR>
 The Cross and the Switchblade</H5>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<a name="1">
<BR>
<DD>In 1963 Dave Wilkerson wrote<I> The Cross and the 
Switchblade,</I> in which he recounted his experiences just a few years earlier 
in New York City.  Rev. Wilkerson was a self-described 
&quot;country preacher&quot; from Philipsburg, a small town in western 
Pennsylvania.  He was married with two children and pastoring a church 
in Philipsburg in 1958.  Rev. Wilkerson saw a story in 
<I>Life</I> magazine about seven gang youths in New York on trial for murder 
and suddenly felt a compelling urge to go to New York and help 
the boys.  
<P>Rev. Wilkerson took many leaps of faith, often unsure as 
to where he would turn next or who would pay tomorrow's bills.  
He met many gang members in Manhattan and Brooklyn, at first 
not knowing how he could help.  His ministry began to spread 
the good news that  homeless, destitute youths were loved and 
could have a better life. It has never departed from that central theme. 
 Often young people only needed someone to show them love 
and caring and lead them to a local church.  Others, however,  
fought in gangs, prostituted themselves, and turned to heroin for comfort. They needed more than just a message, they needed a home 
and constant attention.  
<P>Rev. Wilkerson dreamed of establishing such a home, a 
dream that came true in 1960.  With $100 in the bank, he agreed 
to purchase a large but neglected red-brick Georgian house.  
This house became the first Teen Challenge Center.  From that 
house 20 lowly-paid young workers coordinated efforts to 
evangelize the city's roughest neighborhoods, and to take in youths  
who needed extra attention.  Despite incidents of  stabbings 
and beatings, these workers remained devoted to  those they served. 
<P>The home saved many lives from gang violence and heroin. 
 Rev. Wilkerson believed that the only way to get and 
keep someone off heroin was to have that person receive the baptism 
of the Holy Spirit.  This religious experience is the central focus 
of many Pentecostal denominations.  The baptized Christian 
is taught to &quot;walk with the Holy Spirit,&quot; in close personal 
contact with God.  Rev. Wilkerson found that those who were 
baptized with the Holy Spirit no longer craved heroin.  
<P>
As Rev. Wilkerson was finishing his book, a new Teen 
Challenge Center was opening in Chicago, using the same methods 
as New York Teen Challenge.  In the epilogue he draws this 
lesson: &quot;The Holy Spirit is in charge.  As long as He remains in 
charge, the program will thrive.  The minute we try to do things by our 
own power we will fail.&quot;  Teen Challenge now operates 130 
centers nationwide. 
<P>
The Teen Challenge model is founded on a religious 
component that actually reverses the usual dynamic of religious 
rehabilitation programs.  The usual religious rehabilitation program 
aims to end drug and alcohol abuse  through a religion-based program. 
 Teen Challenge starts with discipleship training which 
battles man's sinful nature and has the side-effect of eradicating drug 
and alcohol abuse.  Teen Challenge firmly sees itself as a 
discipleship training program, and not a drug and alcohol 
rehabilitation program. 
<P>
Still, Teen Challenge focuses its ministry on those whose 
lives will be short and miserable if their addiction is allowed 
to continue. As patterns of addiction have evolved, Teen 
Challenge has changed its focus from teenagers to adults, but the 
philosophy remains the same.  The purpose of the program is not to 
&quot;rehabilitate&quot; in the usual sense of returning the individual to a 
previous state.  The goal  is to create a new person from the olda 
person who does not need addictive substances because he has 
found contentment in a personal relationship with Jesus Christ. 
<P>
<BR>
<a name="2">
<P>
<B>A Growing Program</B>
<P>
Teen Challenge began in 1958 with the tiny but 
powerful ministry of one person who felt the call to leave his 
small-town parsonage for the streets of New York City.  Thirty-eight 
years and thousands of lives later, Teen Challenge is a major 
force among adolescents and adults who have addictive 
problems, and thousands will proudly declare that Teen Challenge 
has  given them a life they never thought possible--a happy life 
free from addictions. 
<P>
As of 1995, Teen Challenge had 130 centers in the 
United States, including Puerto Rico, and a total staff of over 1,500.  
One hundred eleven of the centers are residential. They have a 
 a total capacity of 2,877 and an average occupancy of 2,666. 
 Over 1,000 former addicts completed the program last year. 
<P>
Teen Challenge is also involved in other forms of 
counseling. It answered over 100,000 telephone crisis calls in 1995 
and held almost 14,000 drop-in counseling sessions.  Teen 
Challenge reached 839,000 people in jails, schools, churches, and community 
meetings.
<P>
But drug and alcohol addiction touches the lives of millions of Americans, 
and the mission of Teen Challenge is far from accomplished. 
<P>
<BR>
<a name="3">
<P>
<B>The Nature of Addiction</B>
<P>
Addictions are hard to define because factors such as 
&quot;tolerance,&quot; &quot;physical dependence,&quot; and &quot;reinforcement&quot; are part 
of the equation.  The complexity of defining &quot;addiction&quot; is 
compounded by social, political, and economic factors. 
Addiction to drugs and alcohol is also a medical matter. 
<P>&quot;Addiction,&quot; is not the same as &quot;physical dependence.&quot; 
 Physical dependence is how the body reacts when it lacks a 
drug to which  it has become accustomed.  Heroin has a high rate 
of physical dependence, causing all sorts of physical 
reactions when the body is deprived of it. They are often so violent 
that the addict, for the sake of maintaining bodily equilibrium, 
returns to drug abuse.  Cocaine and marijuana, on the other hand, create 
a relatively low rate of physical dependency. The body does not 
react violently to withdrawal.  Nevertheless, they also are addictive.   
<P>
Cocaine and marijuana are also similar in that they have low 
rates of &quot;tolerance.&quot;  That is, a user 
can take the drug repeatedly over a short time, yet not build up a 
resistance to its effects  Low tolerance rates also mean that the 
user can quit and return to drug use without needing more of it 
to achieve the same high.  For drugs with high tolerance rates, such 
as heroin, tolerance is the second devil working with physical 
dependence.  As the user builds up tolerance, quitting becomes 
more difficult, because the amount to which the user is addicted is 
constantly increasing, giving rise to 
increasingly violent physical reactions upon withdrawal.   
<P>
&quot;Reinforcement&quot; also helps to conceptually define 
addiction.  Used pharmacologically it  refers to whether an 
animal will work for a drug, and how hard and long the animal 
will work.  Animal experiments are not always good predictors 
of human behavior, but in this case the concept seems to apply. 
 Humans will work for a specific dose of a particular drug 
 administered in a particular way.  As the dose, and 
more importantly, method of administration change, the degree 
of reinforcement may also change.  Thus, while dependence 
and tolerance are physical changes in the body, reinforcement is 
a behavioral change. It is affected by social and economic 
factors, drug availability, and how the drug is administered.  
<P>
Therefore, to define &quot;addiction&quot; biologically, one must 
consider a number of factors that contribute to reinforcement and 
 dependence.  One should, furthermore, not forget that 
alcohol is a drug.  Alcohol has a low tolerance rate, a high 
physical dependency rate, and a mid-range rate of reinforcement.  Does 
the high physical dependence contribute to reinforcement?  
No doubt it does, but there are so many other factors that it is 
hard to say that physical dependence creates reinforcement, much 
less addiction.
<P>
With so many variables and causes, modern science 
cannot develop a medical or scientific formula for &quot;curing addiction.&quot; 
It is Teen Challenge's conviction that drug and alcohol abuse 
are products of man's distance from God which must first be 
overcome.
<P>
<P>
<BR>
<a name="4">
<B>The Teen Challenge Method</B>
<P>
Teen Challenge is considered by outsiders to be a religious 
program for the recovery of alcohol and drug addicts, but leaders 
of the movement would disagree with that definition. To them Teen Challenge offers a 
new alternative to rehabilitationso different that it is not 
rehabilitation at all, but a training program for Christian 
discipleship that helps to cleanse away the old human nature and with it 
the addiction.
<P>
Teen Challenge declares its mission is &quot;to evangelize 
people who have life-controlling problems and initiate the 
discipleship process to the point where the student can function as 
a Christian in society, applying spiritually motivated 
Biblical principles to relationships in the family, local church, chosen 
vocation, and the community.  Teen Challenge endeavors to help people 
become mentally sound, emotionally balanced, socially adjusted, 
physically well, and spiritually alive.&quot;
<P>
This mission is developed by various methods, including counseling 
 based on a standardized three-volume collection of class 
materials, &quot;Personal Studies for New Christians,&quot; by David Batty.  The 
counselor barely touches on issues of drugs or alcohol.  Instead, the new 
resident is taught lessons from the Bible on character, life-styles and 
Christian conversion.  Furthermore, the student is encouraged to read other 
Christian books in order to benefit spiritually and emotionally, but also to 
gain practical reading skills.  &quot;God's Plan for the Family&quot; is the subject of 
one class that concentrates on Biblical models of marriage 
and parenthood.   There are also lessons that deal with the 
temptation to leave the program that residents occasionally feel.
<P>
The overall goal of counseling is to prepare a person to 
enter a Christian life-style.  Discussion of drugs or alcohol is  rare. 
 Instead, the patient is taught a new approach to life, as well 
as encouraged to let go of a painful past.  Not only are 
the counseling sessions geared toward the realization of a new 
life-style, but the overall structure of the program, from the first 
day in the center to the reentry program for ex-residents, is 
geared to developing a Christian life-style and world view.  
<P>
Teen Challenge centers consider themselves part of 
the larger Christian church.  Teen Challenge centers are the 
branch of the Church that concentrates on 
&quot;ministry to acutely hurting people.&quot;  This 
is accomplished  through a  five-step process.  The first phase is evangelism.  
Once someone is converted, crisis intervention may be neededthe second step.  
Then, individuals are placed for a three to four month stint in residential induction 
centers.  Beyond this, the student moves to the fourth phase, residence for at least eight months in a training center.  The final step is re-entry, which helps students 
to readjust to society.  
<P>
The residence programs are centered around 
discipleship training with prayer, counseling, Bible reading, worship, 
work activity, meals, meditation, and recreation.  These activities 
are structured around five types of therapy.  In work therapy 
the resident learns the value of work as well as a vocational skill. 
 Group therapy involves the resident living with three others. 
All must take joint responsibility for the upkeep of their room. 
 There are also groups that meet on specific issues, according 
to the needs of the residents.  In individual therapy the goal is 
to &quot;join head and body&quot;to make the student aware of reality 
and  wanting to live in it. Music is another powerful source 
of therapy.  Residents join in worship through music, and in 
the process are drawn into its themes.  The final type of therapy 
is recreational therapy.  Outdoor events and exercise teach 
residents how to use their free time without relying on drugs.  
<P>
The long-range goal of residence and therapy is to move 
the &quot;ex-addict&quot; to the &quot;non-addict&quot; stage. 
 The resident is already an ex-addict upon entry into the program.  
However, he may still relapse into addiction. The final stage of 
non-addiction is achieved when the resident no longer has the desire to use  drugs 
or alcohol.  
<P>
The re-entry programthe final step of Teen Challenge's five 
step processensures that the ex-addict can complete the transition to 
non-addict.  Because it may take years to reach the non-addict stage, Teen 
Challenge stays in touch with many former addicts upon their graduation 
from the program, using the re-entry program to aid them in adjusting to 
the real world.  The focus of re-entry is to help the former addict 
establish healthy relationships with non-addicts and secure employment.  
<P>
<BR>
<a name="5">
<P><B>How Do you Spell Success?</B>
<P>
Teen Challenge's growth in its short history speaks 
volumes about the power of its ministry.  But these numbers are 
merely an outward sign of its effectiveness and high success rate.
<P>
Teen Challenge of Chattanooga, Inc. conducted an 
alumni survey between 1992 and 1994.  The survey was directed by 
Dr. Roger Thompson, head of the Criminal Justice Department 
at the University of Tennessee at Chattanooga.  All the 
alumni surveyed spent their 3-4 month third phase of the program in 
 the Teen Challenge residential induction center in 
Chattanooga sometime between 1979 and 1991.  They then transferred 
to phase four, the training center, at either Cape Girardeau, 
Missouri or Rehrersburg, Pennsylvania.  The survey had a 
50% response rate. 
<P>
The survey's findings are very impressive.  
Eighty-eight percent of those responding named Teen Challenge as 
the treatment program most beneficial in their lives.  Sixty 
percent continued their education after graduation from the program. 
 Sixty percent became members of a local church, and 
76% attended church regularly.  Seventy-two percent were 
employed.  Seventy-six percent were free from the court 
system, quite a reversal from the 60% who were in the court 
system upon entering the program.  Ninety-two percent claimed 
that Teen Challenge had a great impact on their lives.  
Eighty percent credited their ability to abstain from drugs to a 
personal relationship with Jesus Christ.  The statistic that speaks 
volumes, however, is the abstention rate.  A full 67% of 
respondents were completely abstaining from drugs and alcohol.  
<P>
The Chattanooga results are impressive but not surprising. 
 They echo the results found in 1975 by the Department 
of Health, Education, and Welfare.  Dr. Catherine Hess, 
M.D., formerly the assistant chief of the Cancer Control Program 
of the U.S. Public Health Service  studied the class of 
1968 entering the Brooklyn Teen Challenge, who went on 
to Rehrersburg Teen Challenge for their training center phase. 
<P>
Much like in Chattanooga, seventy-two percent of 
graduates continued their education after graduation from Teen 
Challenge.  Seventy-five percent of the graduates were 
currently employed.  Eighty-seven percent of graduates required 
no further treatment after graduating from Teen Challenge.  
Sixty-seven percent regularly attended church.  Only 30% had 
been arrested since graduating.  Moreover, in a statistic 
strikingly similar to the Chattanooga study, 67% of the graduates 
proved themselves drug-free by urinalysis.
<P>
<BR>
<a name="6">
<P>
<B>Changed Lives</B>
<P>
Perhaps the most powerful evidence of a changed life lies 
not in numbers, but in the stories of those whose very lives 
were saved by Teen Challenge.  One such life is that of  James Heurich. James 
began sipping his parents' beers at an early age. His father was an alcoholic. By the age 
of 15, James was drinking bourbon, smoking marijuana, and sniffing up to 20 tubes of glue in a single day.  &quot;My 
younger brother, whom I had started out on drugs, became a heroin addict.  I remember 
the night he died in his sleep in the bed next to mine.&quot;  
<P>
The funeral of James' brother was conducted by the director of the 
Philadelphia Teen Challenge. He prayed with Heurich's father.  After 
37 years of alcoholism, Mr. Heurich put down the bottle forever. 
 For the next eight months, Philadelphia Teen Challenge 
reached out to James Heurich who had entered the program.  James 
is now an ordained minister and Executive Director of San 
Antonio Teen Challenge.  
<P>
John Douglas is another young man whose life was 
changed by Teen Challenge.  He declared in <I>American 
Horizon</I> that, &quot;[i]f Christ had not impacted my life through Teen Challenge, 
I would most likely be dead or locked up.&quot;  Tortured by 
drugs, John knew that he wanted to end his addiction, and he found 
a way out in Teen Challenge.  John entered the Teen 
Challenge program at age 17.  For the first ten days, he was still 
hallucinating from LSD flashbacks.  The patient and caring 
staff finally broke through John's haze, and he completed the 
entire program.  Today John is married with two children, and 
he owns a roofing business.  He credits Teen Challenge with 
his current happy life. 
<P>
These individuals are representative of countless 
others throughout America who share three common attributes.  
They are substance abusers whose lives had been destroyed by 
their habits.  They had tried unsuccessfully to kick their 
habits through various secular programs.  And they have 
found comfort and life control through a structured religiously 
focused treatment programTeen Challenge.
<P>
There is something else that unites them.  The programs that have made the difference between life and death for them are 
at risk.  As long as States exercise licensing authority in ways 
that undermine or corrupt the viability of these programs, a cloud 
of uncertainty will hang over these much-needed organizations. 
<P>At a time when we worry who will help the unfortunates if 
the safety net is removed, we should make it easier for 
these programs to operatenot harder. At a time when concern 
over drug and alcohol abuse is growing, we should foster 
private, voluntary, faith-based programs by removing the state 
licensing requirements that hold such potential for abuse.  This 
will entail a state-by-state examination of the many laws that 
govern drug and alcohol treatment.  Arduous though this task may 
be, it will allow these institutions to become building blocks in 
the creation of a civil society of free and responsible individuals.
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<a name="7">
<P>
<BR>
<B><I>Texas State Authorities Raise Obstacles to Teen Challenge Success</B></I>
<P>
The Alamo was a vivid backdrop and symbolic frame 
of reference for dozens of protesters.  In the crowd of 
largely low-income individuals picketing on a mid-July day 
in 1995, many held signs calling for an end to 
government oppression.  Robert Woodson of the National Center 
for Neighborhood Enterprise, the event organizer, 
exhorted the crowd to take a stand against tyranny, not just 
for themselves, but also for those whose ability to control 
their own lives was threatened by an imperious 
government agency.  This event focused the eyes of the nation on 
Texas where a struggle between  state officials and a small 
faith-based drug and alcohol treatment facility offered 
crucial insight into one of the most important challenges 
facing voluntary self-help programs in America.
<P>
The villain in this story and the object of the 
protesters' wrath is the Texas Commission for Alcohol and 
Drug Abuse (TCADA), which exercises licensing authority 
over all drug and alcohol treatment centers in the state.  
TCADA had recently notified the San Antonio chapter of 
Teen Challenge, the local affiliate of the nationally 
acclaimed drug and alcohol treatment program, that it needed 
a license to continue providing treatment for addiction.  
The fact that San Antonio Teen Challenge had provided 
these service since 1977 was irrelevant to TCADA.
<P>
Under Texas law, any organization that offers 
treatment for drug and alcohol addiction needs a license, and 
TCADA enforced this requirement vigorously.  In order to obtain 
a license, Teen Challenge would have to adopt a 
program that TCADA deemed appropriate.  Not 
surprisingly, TCADA's requirements were different from, and in 
key ways antithetical to, Teen Challenge methods.  So 
Teen Challenge was faced with a stark choice: become a 
creature of the state or halt its program.
<P>
The plight of Teen Challenge came to the attention 
of Marvin Olasky, who published an op-ed in the 
<I>Wall Street Journal</I> in August of 1995 exposing TCADA's 
heavy-handed tactics to a national audience.  At the same time, 
the Institute for Justice offered to represent Teen 
Challenge. The Institute threatened a lawsuit using the 
Religious Freedom Restoration Act to challenge TCADA's 
authority to impose licensing conditions that interfered with 
Teen Challenge's fundamental tenets of faith practiced in 
its drug and alcohol treatment.
<P>
The Institute for Justice began negotiations with 
Texas Governor George W. Bush and with TCADA.  As 
negotiations proceeded, the Institute contacted 
<I>NBC Nightly News</I> and encouraged them to report the story of the 
tension between a group dedicated to self-help through faith 
and secular licensing requirements of a state agency that 
undermined that faith.  NBC soon produced an <I>American 
Agenda</I> feature that was highly favorable to Teen Challenge.  
Not long thereafter, TCADA signed a consent order that 
allows Teen Challenge to continue to operate as it has 
historicallywithout a license. In addition, Governor Bush 
appointed a task force whose members included Teen 
Challenge representatives to review Texas laws and 
regulations and propose reforms that will recognize the importance 
and efficacy of faith-based treatment programs.  
<P>
Although this situation came to a happy resolution, it 
is but one episode in an ongoing saga of how states 
exercise licensing authority to the detriment of voluntary 
self-help drug and alcohol treatment programs, particularly those 
of a faith-based nature.  For as social work and 
psychiatry have exerted their professional presence in this field, 
their secular methodology has become increasingly 
incorporated into licensing requirements imposed by states.  
Teen Challenge has faced similar issues in Oregon, 
Pennsylvania, and Florida in recent years, all of which have 
been resolved at least temporarily so as to allow Teen 
Challenge to continue. But the issue of licensing has left 
unresolved the underlying tension between secular and 
faith-based methods. 
<P>
<BR>
<a name="8">
<P>
 <B><I>Some of the Alternatives</B>
<P>
<P>Alcoholics Anonymous:</I> The modern era of alcohol 
and drug treatment began with Alcoholics Anonymous.  
AA was founded in 1935 by William Wilson, &quot;Bill W.&quot; 
and Robert Holbrook Smith, &quot;Dr. Bob.&quot;  The founders 
believed that the only way to sobriety was to give one's 
life to a Higher Power.  AA treated alcoholism as a 
disease without cure, but with remission.  That remission can 
be maintained only by hard work and moral support, 
and many find that support through AA.  Explosively 
successful from the beginning, AA has grown to over a 
million members, with 67,000 local chapters, plus Al-Anon 
and Alateen, support groups for loved ones and teenage 
children of alcoholics. 
<P>
Alcoholics Anonymous is famous for its 12-step 
method, a method used by many drug and alcohol treatment 
and support groups today.  The 12 steps alcoholics must 
follow to put an end to their alcoholism have a religious 
dimension.  They include such steps as asking God to 
remove one's shortcomings, prayer and meditation, and a 
spiritual awakening. Many attribute the success of AA to its religious natureto the admission that alcoholism can not 
be conquered without the intervention of a Higher Power.
<P>
<I>Medical Model</I>: The general consensus among drug 
and alcohol treatment experts is that alcoholism is a disease.   
 This concept, began with AA and spread to Yale's 
Center of Alcohol Studies, founded in the 1930s.  The Center 
set the pace for medical research and intervention into 
alcoholism by training alcoholism counselors.  The 
disease concept of alcoholism has since that time been the 
leading paradigm in the field.  It has evolved from AA's 
simple concept of  addiction as a lasting condition that one 
must never quit fighting to alcoholism as a medical and 
psychological condition that can be studied empirically.  
Drug abuse, which has exploded in recent decades, has 
therefore been approached by the same model.  
<P>
<P><I>Drug and Psychological Therapy: </I>Drug and alcohol 
addiction are predominantly treated by medical and 
psychological methods.  Most rehabilitation centers follow 
the &quot;Minnesota Model,&quot; which employs drug treatment 
only for detoxification.  The centers often incorporate AA's 
12 steps with inpatient treatment.  The Model integrates 
self-help counseling, involves the family directly and 
continuously, and employs aftercare, or continued contact with 
the patient after graduation from the program.  The 
centers often incorporate AA's 12 steps into the treatment, with 
the first five steps occurring in the inpatient stage, and 
the remaining seven in aftercare. 
<P>
Of all the drug treatments for alcohol, the most popular 
is disulfiram, which goes more commonly by its brand 
name, Antabuse.  Physicians initially treat patients by giving 
them the drug followed by alcohol.  The patient 
experiences acetaldehyde buildup, which induces vomiting, nausea, 
a drop in blood pressure, and a pounding heart.  The 
patients often feel that they will die right there in the doctor's office. 
 Motivated by fear and a regular dosage of Antabuse, 
the patient refrains from drinking alcohol.  
<P>
The second most popular method of drug treatment 
for alcohol is conditioned-reflex treatment.  This 
treatment originated in 1940 when Dr. Walter Voegelin began 
treating alcoholics with Pavlovian conditioning.  The 
physician injects a drug that induces nausea.  Just before the 
patient feels the effects of the drug, the physician gives the 
patient alcohol.  The violent physiological reaction becomes 
associated with alcohol in the patient's mind, and the patient 
will not drink alcohol for several months.  The interim time 
is used for rehabilitation and psychological treatment.
<P>
Psychotherapy has also been used for alcoholics, 
but without good results.  Better results have been attained 
by combining drug therapy with group therapy, 
rehabilitation clinics, and the Minnesota Model.  
<P>
Drug addiction has been treated in similar ways.  
Perhaps the most common medical method of countering 
drug addiction is detoxification.  Detoxification involves 
administering an opiate or barbiturate to the patient at 
regular intervals and slowly reducing dosages.  An 
in-hospital detoxification usually takes two weeks, while an 
outpatient detoxification takes four to six weeks. Detoxification 
is successful in temporarily stalling addiction so that 
other treatment may be administered, but rarely causes 
long-term cessation of drug use without other interventions. 
<P>
Psychiatric hospitals are sometimes used in 
conjunction with detoxification.  Psychiatric hospital programs 
vary: elements include the frequency of patient-psychiatrist 
contact, the focus of daily activity, whether individual or 
group, and the use of psychiatric drugs.  Psychiatric 
hospitalization is good for those with serious mental disorders, but 
it is not particularly successful or cost-effective for those 
with no such disorder.
<P>
Psychiatric drugs, among others, are also used in 
outpatient therapy.   However, the more popular form of 
outpatient therapy is drug maintenance.  Drug 
maintenance therapy differs from detoxification in that it requires 
a much longer term of treatment, focusing on one of 
three areas: (1) treating withdrawal symptoms and cravings, 
(2) creating high cross-tolerance so that the addict can 
no longer feel any &quot;high&quot; from using the illicit drug, and 
(3) maintaining abstinence by drug antagonists, which 
neutralize the effects of the addictive drug.  The best 
known drug maintenance therapy is methadone, which is used 
as a substitute for heroin.  It can be given in doses to 
either treat cravings or to create cross-tolerance.  Methadone 
has met with mixed results, as have most types of drug 
maintenance therapy.
<P>
Besides medical treatments, psychological and 
social treatments are also used for drug addictions. 
Psychological treatments include psychotherapy, behavior 
therapy, and group therapy.  The classical Freudian 
psychotherapy has not been effective in treating drug addiction.  
Behavior therapy, in which the patient unlearns maladjusted 
behavior and relearns functional behavior, has been more 
successful.  Group therapy, which entails three different 
kinds of therapy, has been yet more successful, but with 
some mixed results.  Group therapy involves couples, 
families, and encounter groups.  Encounter groups bring 
addicts together to emotionally struggle through and work 
out their problems, a method that is definitely effective in 
the short-run, but with uncertain effects over long periods 
of time.  
<P>
Social intervention takes a different route.  Some 
groups, like Alcoholics Anonymous, maintain self-help 
programs with addict support groups run by ex-addicts.  
Others, known as &quot;day care&quot; centers, involve the addict in 
a daytime program.  Therapeutic communities are like 
day care centers, except that the addict lives in the community. 
 They vary tremendously, but all have the same 
basic phases of admission, residence, and post-residence 
reentry into society.  The residence phase involves a 
structured program that modifies the environment of the 
patient, assigning work tasks and holding group meetings.  
The results of such programs are very mixed.
<P>
<BR>
<a name="9">
<P>
<BR>
<B>For more information contact:</I>
<P>
<B>Teen Challenge 
National Training &amp; Resource Center
</B><BR>
P.O. Box 1015
<BR>
Springfield, MO 65801
<BR>
(800) 814-5729
<P>
<BR>
<B>Teen Challenge of South Texas</B>
<BR>3850 S. Loop 1604 West
<BR>
San Antonio, TX 78264
<BR>
(210) 624-2075</B>
<P>
