<font size=+1><i>Foundation Watch Vol. I No.9</i></font><P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>October, 1996</B></FONT><p>
<center><font size=-1><a href="#green">Inside the Green Mafia</a> | <a href="#pew">The Pew Charitable Trusts</a> | <a href="#money">Money Laundered by the Tides Foundation</a> | <a href="#catalysts">Environmental Catalysts</a> 
| <a href="#ford">Ford's Better Idea</a> | <a href="#heinz"> | <a href="#family">Rockefeller's Green Family Values</a> 
| <a href="#jones">Keeping up with W.Alton Jones</a> | <a href="#mouth">Green Giving by the Mouth of the South</a> | <a href="#piper">She Who Pays the Piper Calls the Tune</a> | <a href="#editor">Letters to the Editor</a></center> 
</font><hr>
<a name="green">
<center><h2>INSIDE THE GREEN MAFIA: THE BIG ENVIRONMENTALIST GRANTMAKERS</h2>
<h3>by Jonathan Adler</h3></center>
<p>
Environmentalism today is Big Business.  By some estimates, the 
environmental movement commands revenues of nearly one-half billion
dollars annually, and at least a dozen of its organizations have
annual budgets in excess of $20 million. Notwithstanding environmentalist
claims, this wealth is not an accurate indicator of grass-roots
support.  Membership levels at many environmental groups have
been static or fallen in recent years, and membership dues provide
less than half of a typical group's funds, although they remain
a significant source of revenue.  The major environmentalist groups
headquartered in Washington, DC look elsewhere for the vast sums
they require to support their large staffs and expensive advocacy
campaigns.  Corporations, government agencies and private philanthropic
foundations now provide major grant support to the movement. 
This report will focus on the role of foundation support.  (For
a full discussion of the environmental movement see Jonathan Adler,
Environmentalism at the Crossroads, Capital Research Center, 1995,
299 pages.)
<P>
According to a 1992 study conducted by the Conservation
Fund, private foundations account for approximately one-fifth
of environmental group funding.  By virtue of their concentrated
funding, foundations have become highly influential in the environmental
movement.  However, more than money is involved.  When an environmental
group receives active foundation assistance, the financial reward
is only the most tangible aspect of support.  As the Conservation
Fund study concludes:
<P>
The importance of foundations goes well beyond the
giving of money.  Leaders depend on foundations for programmatic
ideas, information on productive  networking with other groups,
occasional technical support, and the sense of legitimacy and
prestige that comes with foundation grants.  Well-funded organizations
gain the attention of policymakers simply by virtue of the recognition
they receive from national grant makers.
<P>
In recent years foundation funders have moved from
behind the scenes.  Not content to be silent partners, grantmakers
have discovered that they can coordinate lobbying and set the
agenda of diverse environmental groups by coordinating the distribution
of foundation grants.  This is the enviable role of the Environmental
Grantmakers Association, a so-called &quot;affinity group&quot;
of the Council on Foundations.  An EGA conference brochure puts
it this way:  &quot;In 1987, a group of environmental grantmakers
met in Washington, D.C. to discuss common interests and to learn
about each other's specific programs.&quot;  Among the group's
stated purposes: &quot;To promote recognition that the environment
and its inhabitants  are endangered by unsustainable human activities;&quot;
&quot;To facilitate communication, foster cooperation, and develop
collaboration among active and potential members;&quot; and &quot;To
increase the resources available to address environmental concerns.&quot;

<P>
In January 1995, EGA had 182 members from private,
corporate, and community foundations.  Housed in the offices of
the Rockefeller Family Foundation in New York City, EGA's &quot;Management
Committee&quot; in 1994 included representatives from eight foundations
-- Island,Nathan Cummings, Surdna, C.S. Mott, Compton, Bullitt,
MacArthur, and Hewlett -- and one corporation, Apple Computer.
 EGA members meet annually at retreats and conferences, share
information on grantmaking, and strategize about how to achieve
environmental goals.  As the leftist magazine Mother Jones has
noted, &quot;By deciding which organizations get money, the grant-makers
help set the agenda of the environmental movement and influence
the programs that activists carry out.&quot;  EGA coordinator
Donald Ross, a director of the grantmaking Rockefeller Family
Fund, asserts that &quot;funders have a major role to play&quot;
in determining the environmental policy agenda.  
<P>
At EGA's 1994 annual meeting many members agreed
to devote more funds to issues of population and consumption,
a theme of the meeting.  Topics at the 1992 annual retreat included
&quot;Population and the Environment,&quot; &quot;Environmentally
Responsible Investing,&quot; &quot;Environmental Education, K-12,&quot;
&quot;Environment and Spirituality,&quot; and &quot;1993, Year
of Indigenous Peoples.&quot; Few of EGA's professional grantmakers
know how their organizations' founders created the wealth they
freely dispense.  Indeed, they do not seem to appreciate how the
free enterprise system makes wealth accumulation possible.  In
his keynote address to the 1992 EGA retreat, zoologist and environmental
author David Suzuki offered a remarkable commentary that illustrates
how intellectually disconnected environmentalists are from the
wealth of their foundation patrons.  Suzuki observed:
<P>
Economics is a very chauvinistic invention -- and
I don't mean male chauvinist -- it is a species chauvinistic idea.
 No other species on earth, and there may be 30 million of them,
has had the nerve to put forth a concept called economics, in
which one species, us, declares the right to put value on everything
else on earth, in the living and non-living world.
<P>
Although some EGA members are less radical in their
analysis and prescriptions, the organization has helped steer
environmental grantmaking leftward toward more government control
over the economy.  Today most foundation giving for &quot;environmental
protection&quot; is used to prop up nonprofit organizations that
have become key parts of a Washington establishment dedicated
to continued expansion of the regulatory state.  Profiles of some
of the most powerful grantmaking foundations supporting the environmental
cause follow:<BR>
<P>
<a name="pew"> 
<h4>THE BIGGEST AND BADDEST:
THE PEW CHARITABLE TRUSTS</h4><BR>
<P>
Pew appears to be the largest environ-<BR>
  mental grantmaker.  In 1993 alone it <BR>
  donated $35 million to green causes.  As a leader in the field
it even goes so far as to conceive of projects for environmental
groups to undertake in order to attract funding from other private
foundations.  Pew's funding focuses on three areas: global climate
change, pollution prevention, and forest and marine conservation.
 It also has launched major programs to promote public advocacy
and civic participation in government policymaking and it supports
&quot;environmental education&quot; using the school curriculum
and Boy Scout style recruiting to mobilize children for the cause.
<P>
Pew funds have also spurred development of new tactics
including the formation of environmental coalitions and regional
campaigns.  A recent $150,000 Pew grant to a project named the
Global Action Plan for the Earth seeks to &quot;support the development
and delivery of a program educating children about how to live
environmentally sustainable lives.&quot;  Another grant of $120,000
over two years went to the Humane Society of the United States
(HSUS) to support a project entitled &quot;Theological Education
to Meet the Environmental Challenge.&quot;  It is aimed at influencing
seminaries and divinity schools on population and environmental
issues.  HSUS, contrary to popular belief, does not run animal
shelters.  It is an animal rights advocacy organization that opposes
hunting, circuses, rodeos, and marine mammal parks.  Its officers
have recently come under fire for using the society to promote
their private financial interests.
<P>
The scope of environmental support by the Pew Charitable
Trusts may be gauged by a review of grants it made in 1995: 
<P>
Alaska Conservation Foundation (15 months)      $470,000
<P>
American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy
(2-years)   $325,000 
<P>
Aspen Institute (9 months) $1,015,000 
<P>
Business for Social Responsibility Education Fund
    $200,000 
<P>
Chesapeake Bay Foundation (2 years)      $200,000
<P>
Christian Environmental Association (2 years)   
  $175,000 
<P>
Christianity Today (18 months) $175,000 
<P>
Environmental Defense Fund $110,000 
<P>
Environmental Information Center (2 grants)     
$986,000 
<P>
Greater Yellowstone Coalition (2 years)      $600,000
<P>
National Audubon Society (4 grants, 2 years)    
 $2,015,000
<P>
National Religious Partnership for the Environment
(18 months)   $323,000 
<P>
Natural Resources Defense Council (9 months)    
 $625,000 
<P>
Sierra Club Foundation (2 grants, 9 months)     
$1,125,000
<P>
Worldwatch Institute (2 years) $200,000 
<P>
World Wildlife Fund (3 grants, 2 years)      $1,360,000
<BR>
<P>
In 1988, the Foundation established the Pew Fellows
Program in Conservation and the Environment.  Rather like the
MacArthur Foundation &quot;genius grants,&quot; this program was
intended to fulfill what Pew identified as &quot;a critical need
to identify and support a new generation of scholar-scientists
who would apply their special knowledge and skills directly to
pressing environmental problems.&quot;  The Foundation annually
awards ten three-year $150,000 fellowships.  More recently, however,
Pew has changed its definition of likely recipients, and the fellowships
now encompass &quot;outstanding scientists, researchers and conservation
activists.&quot;  Why the change?  Perhaps because Pew fellowships
increasingly go to environmental activists with limited scientific
credentials.  Recent Pew Fellows include Michael J. Bean and David
S. Wilcove of the Environmental Defense Fund, Johanna H. Wald
of the Natural Resources Defense Council, Victor M. Sher of the
Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund, and Carl Safina of the National
Audubon Society. 
<P>
One current Pew scholar is Theo Colburn, a zoologist
at the World Wildlife Fund and co-author of Our Stolen Future,
a controversial new book which alleges that synthetic chemicals
may be responsible for such developmental and reproductive problems
in humans as low sperm counts, impotence, and homosexuality. 
Another Pew scholar is Donella Meadows, co-author of the infamously
wrong 1972 doomsday report The Limits to Growth. Another Pew Fellow
is Reed F. Noss, who established the radical Wildlands Project
with Earth First! founder Dave Foreman.  The Wildlands project
is an effort to &quot;restore&quot; over half of the United States
to its &quot;natural&quot; condition.  Its mission statement says:
<P>
"We live for the day when grizzlies in Chihuahua
have an unbroken connection to grizzlies in Alaska; when gray
wolf populations are continuous from New Mexico to Greenland;
when vast, unbroken forests and flowing plains again thrive and
support pre-Colombian populations of plants and animals.&quot;
<P>
Pew Fellows are nominated by 37 &quot;leaders in
the conservation  field&quot; who each submit two candidates.
 Candidates must then apply for a fellowship.  The  nominators
include many representatives from environmental organizations
that are recipients of Pew funds, including the Worldwatch Institute,
World Wildlife Foundation, Natural Resources Defense Council,
Environmental Defense Fund, and the National Audubon Society.
 Beginning in 1996, Pew Fellows will be selected who focus on
the &quot;sustainable utilization&quot; and conservation of marine
resources. 
<P>
Pew Fellow Michael J. Bean, chair of the wildlife
program at the Environmental Defense Fund, currently directs the
Pew Scholars Program, and he sits on the Advisory Committee that
evaluates applications.  That committee also includes Zero Population
Growth founder Paul Ehrlich, sustainable development guru Herman
E. Daly, author of the no-growth Steady-State Economics, and Kathryn
Saterson of the World Wildlife Fund. 
<P>
Another ambitious Pew project is Environmental Strategies,
since renamed the Environmental Information Center.  Conceived
in 1993 by Joshua Reichert, Pew's environmental director and a
veteran of the movement, its stated mission is to help environmental
groups &quot;conduct public education campaigns on priority national
environmental issues&quot; and &quot;to improve the campaigning
skills of national, regional and local environmental groups.&quot;
In truth, the Environmental Information Center is controlled
by a mixed board of environmental and foundation leaders and it
is supposed to act as a &quot;command center&quot; coordinating
lobbying by Washington, D.C. environmental advocacy groups.  &quot;We
started [the Environmental Information Center] because no organization
was doing what we thought needed to be done,&quot; Reichert told
writer Mark Dowie.  But others disagree.  Reflecting the resentment
that environmental groups must feel at attempts by funders to
control their agenda, Jim Maddy, then president of the League
of Conservation Voters, responded, &quot;The idea that what we
need right now is yet another organization to perform the function
of a headquarters doesn't strike me as the solution to our problems.&quot;
<P>
Pew supplied the Tides Foundation with a two-year,
$650,000 start-up grant to administer funds to get the Center
going.  The W. Alton Jones Foundation added $125,000 and the Rockefeller
Family Fund supplied another $60,000.  Last year, Pew gave the
Center close to $1 million.  The Environmental Information Center
is meant to sell policies, not provide research or analysis. 
As Reichert has explained, &quot;I don't want someone who knows
the facts, or can articulate them persuasively.  I want someone
who wants to win and knows how.&quot;  The ideal project leader,
he told Dowie, would be Clinton campaign consultant James Carville.
<P>
The Center claims that its D.C. office is &quot;the
'war room' for a massive public education campaign to alert Americans
that the new majority in Congress is teaming up with powerful
special interests to roll back 25 years of environmental protections.&quot;
 To broaden support for environmental regulation, it is trying
to build coalitions with local government officials, religious
leaders, and &quot;children's advocacy groups.&quot;  The Center
has been particularly active in promoting the work of the Evangelical
Environmental Network, a spin-off of the liberal Evangelicals
for Social Action, a group that argues that the Endangered Species
Act is biblically ordained. According to the Network, &quot;the
threat to the Act threatens the core of our faith.&quot;  The
Environmental Information Center's has also been an ardent opponent
of the House Republicans' &quot;Contract With America.&quot; 
<P>
The Center's 501(c)(4) lobby, the American Community
Protection Association, has campaigned against the Contract's
property-rights legislation by running ads in publications like
Roll Call, a Washington, D.C. biweekly newspaper that focuses
primarily on the internal operations of Congress.  &quot;'Takings'
provisions would interfere with state and local decision making
and could inflict new and unlimited funding mandates on state
and local governments.&quot;  In fact, the provisions, which provide
compensation for government actions diminishing property values,
apply only to federal laws and explicitly exempt federal rules
that reinforce state and local laws, including common-law protections
of public health and safety.  By targeting a publication widely
read by members of Congress and their staffs, the advertisements
must influence how they will think about property rights legislation.
<BR>
<P>
<a name="money">
<h4>MONEY LAUNDERED BY
THE TIDES FOUNDATION</h4><BR>
<P>
The Tides Foundation is a unique 
funder of environmentalist causes. 
Founded in 1976 by activist Drummond Pike it aims &quot;to link
diverse individuals seeking  social justice, creative new approaches
to economic enterprise, and an enlightened stewardship of our
national environment.&quot;  In particular, &quot;The Foundation
is interested in supporting efforts which demonstrate the value
of sustainable agricultural techniques, groups working to promote
the preservation of the Earth's remaining wetlands and rainforests,
and the struggles of indigenous people around the world who have
pioneered ways of `living gently' on the land.&quot;
<P>
Tides is no traditional foundation. Legally, it
is a grantmaking charity, not a philanthropic foundation.  In
practice, this means that Tides is both a grantmaker and a grant-taker,
raising money in order to support assorted projects undertaken
by those who come to it.  Tides' money comes from other foundations,
individual and corporate grants, and even government sources.
 This dual role gives Tides an unusual place among foundation
funders of environmental groups.
<P>
The Tides Foundation's division of activities reflects
its twin purposes: grantmaking and project management.  This peculiar
structure enables it to handle so-called &quot;pass-through&quot;
grants for those who want to keep their contributions secret.
 Tides will work with donors to channel their funds to preferred
causes.  Typically, donors give a minimum of $25,000 annually
to Tides.  At the donor's direction, Tides will then steer these
funds to the donor's chosen cause, whether or not it is affiliated
with Tides, and it will charge a percentage service fee.  Tides
is widely credited with having provided the grant that enabled
the Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC) to hire Fenton Communications,
a public relations firm, to promote NRDC's alarmist report on
the pesticide Alar.  Many donors choose this way of working with
Tides because it can provide them with total anonymity.  &quot;Anonymity
is very important to most of the people we work with,&quot; Tides
president Drummond Pike explained to the Chronicle of Philanthropy.
<P>
The management side of Tides, known as the Tides
Center, became a separate entity in April 1996.  It helps small
start-up groups handle their organizational affairs.  This projects
management task is the heart of Tides' work.  These start-up group
projects are technically adjuncts of the Foundation because they
use Tides' non-profit status as their own.  This spares new groups
from the chore of completing IRS paperwork to achieve independent
tax-exempt status.  It also enables them to benefit from the Tides'
oversight and managerial expertise.  Tides can offer new groups
practical experience in managing particular programs.  It can
help them select a health insurance provider and other outside
contractors.  Funding is channeled through Tides, which charges
a percentage fee for its services.  These fees pay for Tides'
operating expenses. 
<P>
Groups that work with Tides commend the concept.
 &quot;I think it is a bargain for a small start-up organization
to not have to worry about a lot of the vital details of becoming
an institution that Tides can take care of for you,&quot; commented
Kenneth Cook, president of the Environmental Working Group (EWG),
a current Tides Project.  EWG raised about $1.3 million in 1994
and paid Tides approximately $65,000 in service fees.  The Environmental
Information Center also relied on the Tides Center before its
obtained independent non-profit status. 
<P>
In 1994 Tides distributed $11 million in grants.
 These went to an assortment of causes, only some of which were
environmental.  Tides' environmental-related grants listed in
its 1994-5 annual report include the following:<BR>
<P>
Animal Welfare Institute  $19,106 
<P>
Citizens Clearinghouse for Hazardous Wastes     
$17,816 
<P>
Environmental Action Foundation $15,000 
<P>
Environmental Support Center $25,000 
<P>
Environmental Working Group $46,909 
<P>
Essential Information  $149,3000 
<P>
Friends of the Earth  $260,000 
<P>
Greenhouse Crisis Foundation $50,000 
<P>
Greenpeace, USA  $22,309 
<P>
Rainforest Action Network $32,532 
<P>
Rocky Mountain Institute $20,000 
<P>
In 1994, Tides projects received an additional $22
million from outside foundations, individuals and corporations.
 In 1993, nearly one-third of the Tides Center's 180 projects
dealt with the environment.  These included the Student Environmental
Action Coalition, the Institute for Deep Ecology Education, and
the Biotechnology Working Group.  Current environmental projects
include, among others, the Environmental Working Group, the Military
Toxics Project, the Biotechnology Working Group, Biodiversity
Action Network, Forest Guardians, the Environmental and Economic
Justice Project, and the Institute for Global Communications,
which operates the EcoNet on-line computer network.
<P>
In the spring of 1996, the two sides of Tides formally
separated.  Both, however, moved into a former hospital complex,
renamed the Thoreau Center for Sustainability, located at San
Francisco's historic Presidio National Park, which anchors one
side of the Golden Gate Bridge (Tides leases the complex from
the National Park Service).  Tides's moving and renovation costs
for the Thoreau Center were approximately $5 million. Tides created
a special for-profit subsidiary that took advantage of tax breaks
provided for historical preservation.
<P>
Besides Tides, the Thoreau Center houses other nonprofit
organizations, several of which are Tides projects.  Center tenants
include the Energy Foundation, Institute for Global Communications,
Military Toxics Project, Social Venture Network, and the California
office of the Wilderness Society.  Tides employs about 300 staff
in its offices at the Presidio, in Washington, D.C., and elsewhere.
<BR>
<P>
<a name="catalysts">
<h4>OTHER ENVIRONMENTAL
'CATALYSTS'</h4><BR>
<P>
Pew and Tides are not alone in acting 
as catalysts to create new environmental
groups and campaigns.  For example, in 1982 the John D.
and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation provided a $15 million grant
to launch the World Resources Institute, a Washington, D.C.-based
nonprofit research organization which consults for governments
and for nongovernmental organizations around the world, especially
in developing nations, and which focuses on such global issues
as population, climate and sustainable development.  WRI's first
president was the ubiquitous James Gustave &quot;Gus&quot; Speth,
a founder of the Natural Resources Defense Council, former head
of President Jimmy Carter's Council on Environmental Quality (where
he oversaw production of the Global 2000 report which predicted
imminent resource exhaustion), and currently head of the United
Nations Development Program (see &quot;Making Americans Pay: The
MacArthur Foundation's Plan For A Global IRS&quot; in Foundation
Watch, vol.I, no.8).  
<P>
Speth has been a prominent exponent of the concept
of &quot;sustainable development&quot; and he has focused his
attention on energy-related issues.  Following the Persian Gulf
conflict, for instance, Speth, then at WRI, called for a new national
energy strategy.  Writing in the Los Angeles Times, he demanded
contradictory policies that would &quot;guarantee an affordable
supply of energy&quot; while increasing taxes on fossil fuels
because &quot;at the root of our problem is America's addiction
to cheap energy.&quot;  WRI's annual revenues, almost $14 million
in 1994, have since come from such private grantmakers as the
Joyce, Charles Stewart Mott, Rockefeller and Surdna foundations
and the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.
<P>
<P>
<a name="ford">
<h4>FORD'S BETTER IDEA</h4><BR>
<P>
Just as MacArthur established WRI, the 
Ford Foundation is credited with founding
in 1952 Resources for the Future, the foremost nonprofit
environmental research organization in Washington, D.C.  Ford
also provided in 1970 the seed money for the Natural Resources
Defense Council, the environmental litigation group known for
the Alar scare which alleged potential health threats from pesticide
residues on apples.  Ford has provided major funding for most
of the environmental organizations that use litigation to achieve
changes in public policy, including the Sierra Club Legal Defense
Fund, Environmental Defense Fund, and Southern California Center
for Law in the Public Interest. <BR>
<P>
<a name="heinz">
<h4>HEINZ'S 57 VARIETIES
OF ENVIRONMENTALISM</h4>
<P>
The Heinz Endowments have become 
another major player in 
environmental grantmaking.  They put up $20 million in 1995 to launch
the Heinz Center for Science, Economics and the Environment in
memory of the late Pennsylvania Republican Senator H. John Heinz
III. Theresa Heinz, the Senator's widow and a vice-chairman of
the Environmental Defense Fund, has made the environment a central
concern of the Heinz Endowments.  Upon announcing the Center's
establishment Theresa Heinz ,by now remarried to U.S. Senator
John Kerry (D-MA) (who did not give a penny to charity in 1995),
explained, &quot;This center will be a middle ground where the
major stakeholders in environmental policy can be jointly challenged
to think long-term and to forge a durable consensus for action
based on sound scientific and economic principles.&quot;  The
Center's president is William Merrell, a distinguished oceanographer,
and its board includes Fred Krupp, executive director of the Environmental
Defense Fund, John Sawhill, president of the Nature Conservancy,
Enron Corporation chairman Kenneth Lay, Carnegie Mellon president
Robert Mehrabian, Princeton University biologist Simon A. Levin,
and Paul O'Neill, chairman of ALCOA. 
<P>
Beginning in 1994, the Endowments announced recipients
of the Heinz Awards.  In 1994, the winners of the Heinz Award
for the Environment were the doomsayers Paul and Anne Ehrlich,
who were cited for &quot;their thoughtful studies of difficult
environmental issues.&quot;  Paul Ehrlich is the author of the
1968 book The Population Bomb, which proclaimed that &quot;The
battle to feed all of humanity is over...In the 1970s the world
will undergo famines - hundreds of millions of  people are going
to starve to death in spite of any crash programs embarked upon
now.&quot;  The Ehrlichs recently co-authored a sequel, The Population
Explosion which predicted more of the same.  Paul Ehrlich is also
the founder of Zero Population Growth, an organization dedicated
to the global control of population.  According to Heinz, the
Ehrlichs' &quot;prescriptions, sometimes misrepresented as draconian,
are rooted in the same Judeo-Christian principles that are the
source of the Ehrlichs' profound ethic of stewardship.&quot; 
Of course, the Ehrlichs' predicted population &quot;die-backs&quot;
have never occurred. 
<P>
The 1995 Heinz Award went to Dr. Herbert Needleman,
guru of the &quot;get-the-lead-out&quot; movement.  Needleman,
a pediatrician and child psychologist, is the founder of the Alliance
to End Childhood Lead Poisoning and the author of several controversial
articles on lead's impact on children.  All scientists recognize
that exposure to lead can have a serious impact on child development.
 Needleman, however, has maintained that the impacts occur at
levels lower than is generally accepted by many experts.<BR>
<P>
<a name="family">
<h4>ROCKEFELLER'S GREEN
FAMILY VALUES</h4>

<P>
The Rockefeller Family Fund (RFF) is
a veteran funder of environmental 
causes.  Founded in 1967, the Fund has over $44 million in assets
and is organized into five programs: Citizen Education and Participation,
Economic Justice for Women, Institutional Responsiveness, Self-Sufficiency,
and the largest program, Environment.  RFF is but one of several
Rockefeller family foundations supporting environmental causes.
 The Rockefeller Foundation, Rockefeller Brothers Fund, American
Conservation Association, and Jackson Hole Preserve together contributed
over $12 million to environmental causes in 1992 (John D. Rockefeller,
IV, a member of the Rockefeller family, has a vacation home in
Jackson Hole, Wyoming in which President Clinton has vacationed).
<P>
The Rockefeller Family Fund is the most prominent
of these in the area of environmental giving.  While RFF grants
are made to &quot;organizations which traditionally enjoy popular
support, such as universities, museums, hospitals, or endowed
institutes,&quot; the Fund also supports &quot;advocacy programs
that are action-oriented and likely to yield tangible public policy
results.&quot;  Moreover, it seeks to promote &quot;progressive&quot;
causes while countering the &quot;political right.&quot;  Most
of its environmental giving is of this sort. 
<P>
One particular interest of the Rockefeller Family
Fund is encouraging &quot;whistleblowing&quot; [i.e., snitching]
and environmental activism [i.e., politics] by civil servants.
 As RFF director Donald Ross explained in a 1994 letter to members
of the Environmental Grantmakers' Association, the group whose
work he helps coordinate:
<P>
Underlying many successful news releases, lawsuits,
and blockbuster reports and testimony is information provided
by insiders: public employees who rejected conformity, abandoned
the get-ahead, go-along philosophy of government service and blew
the whistle.  Whistleblowing is always important, but it becomes
even more so when public policies are in dispute.
<P>
Toward this end, the Fund in 1993 supported the
Government Accountability Project ($60,000) and Association of
Forest Service Employees for Environmental Ethics ($20,000), two
nonprofits that promote whistleblowing, particularly when it produces
litigation.  As Ross notes, &quot;The one-two punch of inside
whistleblowers and outside litigators remains potent.&quot; 
<P>
Among the environmental groups that received RFF
grants in 1994 were the following: 
<P>
Alaskan Conservation Foundation $40,000 
<P>
Center for Auto Safety  $25,000 
<P>
Citizens Clearinghouse for Hazardous Wastes     
$30,000 
<P>
Clean Water Action  $25,000 
<P>
Clean Water Fund  $25,000 
<P>
Environmental Information Center $30,000 
<P>
Environmental Support Center $30,000 
<P>
Friends of the Earth Foundation $25,000 
<P>
Mineral Policy Center  $25,000
<P>
Mothers and Others for a Livable Planet      $30,000
<P>
Ozone Action, Inc.  $30,000
<P>
Western Ancient Forests Campaign $30,000 
<P>
<P>
Other Rockefeller foundations also support organized
environmental activism.  In 1992, the American Conservation Association
gave $90,000 to the Natural Resources Defense Council, $90,000
to the Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund, and $75,000 to the Wilderness
Society. In 1992, the Rockefeller Brothers Fund supported the
Worldwatch Institute ($525,000), American Farmland Trust ($1,000,000),
and Environmental Law Institute ($120,000 [3-year]). In 1993,
the Jackson Hole Preserve funded the Greater Yellowstone Coalition
($20,000), National Wildlife Federation ($10,000), and National
Park Foundation ($125,000).<BR>
<P>
<a name="jones">
<h4>KEEPING UP WITH
W. ALTON JONES</h4>
<P>
<P>
The W. Alton Jones Foundation is 
devoted exclusively to two issues, &quot;to 
protect the Earth's life-support systems from environmental
harm and to eliminate the possibility of nuclear war.&quot;  Like
the Pew Charitable Trusts, the foundation is the product of oil
industry wealth.  In 1995 it made grants of nearly $20 million,
with over 60 percent going to environmental organizations and
causes.  Although based in Charlottesville, Virginia the Jones
Foundation is well-connected to Washington, D.C.'s environmental
establishment.  Debra Callahan, the newly appointed president
of the League of Conservation Voters, was formerly the foundation's
environmental grass-roots coordinator.  Foundation director John
Peterson Myers is a former senior vice president at the National
Audubon Society.  George Perkovich, a foundation program director,
was a prominent defender of Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary who
was widely criticized for using outside consultants to evaluate
media coverage of her Department.
<P>
W. Alton Jones's &quot;Sustainable World Program&quot;
provides funding for environmental groups.  Foundation boilerplate
says it &quot;supports efforts that will ensure that human activities
do not undermine the quality of life of future generations and
do not erode the Earth's capacity to support living organisms.&quot;
 According to the Foundation, this is achieved through &quot;a
tight focus on issues whose resolution will determine how habitable
the planet remains over the next century and beyond.&quot;The
W. Alton Jones Foundation has become intimately tied to the campaign
against synthetic chemicals that, it is claimed, may damage human
and animal hormone systems.  This campaign, largely based on speculative
claims and anecdotal evidence, was boosted by publication in 1996
of the book Our Stolen Future.  Co-author John Peterson Myers
is a director of the foundation.  Another co-author, Theo Colburn
of the World Wildlife Fund, had been a foundation staff scientist.
 Our Stolen Future calls for a dramatic reduction in chemical
use and far stricter regulatory controls on industry.  The authors
urge consumers to buy only organic vegetables and to stop microwaving
food in plastic containers.  Many scientists reject as unproven
the book's central charge that hormone-disrupting chemicals are
a major public health risk, and the book's claims have been criticized
in the New York Times and Wall Street Journal.
<P>
In 1995 W. Alton Jones Foundation made environmental
grants to:
<P>
<P>
Alliance to Save Energy (2 years) $150,000
<P>
Conservation International Foundation (2 years) 
      $325,000 
<P>
Environmental Law Institute (2 years)      $200,000
<P>
Environmental Working Group (2 grants)      $245,000
<P>
Friends of the Earth (2 years) $200,000
<P>
Mothers &amp; Others for a Livable Planet      $75,000
<P>
National Religious Partnership for the Environment
    $150,000 
<P>
Natural Resources Defense Council (2 years)     
$300,000 
<P>
Physicians for Social Responsibility  $75,000 
<P>
Rainforest Alliance (2 years) $239,000
<P>
Sierra Club Foundation  $175,000 
<P>
Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund (2 grants)      $200,000
<P>
Southern Environmental Law Center (2 years)     
$100,000
<P>
Taxpayers for Common Sense Foundation      $75,000
<P>
Union of Concerned Scientists (2 years)      $300,000
<P>
Wilderness Society  $100,000 
<P>
World Resources Institute (2 years) $200,000<BR>
<P>
Like many of the other environmental grantmakers
the Jones foundation has encouraged environmental advocacy groups
to cooperate with one another and coordinate their policy objectives.
 These efforts &quot;usually take the form of coordinated grants
to multiple institutions, each of which focuses on one or more
components of an overall campaign. . . .&quot; Once an initiative
is underway, the Foundation accepts grant proposals from organizations
that want to participate.  The Jones Foundation has also supported
non-environmental groups engaged in environmental work.  For instance,
in 1993 the Foundation made a $15,000 grant to the National Taxpayers
Union Foundation to oppose environmentally-destructive corporate
subsidies.  <BR>
<P>
<a name="mouth">
<h4>GREEN GIVING BY 
THE 'MOUTH OF THE SOUTH'</h4><BR>
<P>
The Turner Foundation is perhaps the 
newest foundation to dedicate big 
money to environmental issues.  Media mogul Ted Turner hopes
his foundation, launched in 1990, will become the largest philanthropy
devoted to environmental and population issues.  In 1994 it gave
$5 million to environmental causes, a figure sure to climb.  Unfortunately,
the cable pioneer who once prided himself on his feisty independence
of mind (he tried to take over CBS with Senator Jesse Helms in
the 1980's) now seems to have fallen victim to conventional thinking
about the environment and population. Turner explains, &quot;We
are literally in a fight to save the humans.&quot;  He told the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, &quot;I see the whole field of environmentalism
and population as nothing more than the survival of the human
species.  I have wanted to have some bumper stickers made up saying,
`Save the  Humans.'  At the bottom of it all, we are trying to
save ourselves.&quot;  
<P>
The executive director of the Foundation is Peter
Bahouth, former head of Greenpeace USA, widely regarded as the
most radical of the major environmental organizations.  Greenpeace
is well known for its high-profile campaign to end whaling worldwide.
 It also has called for a complete phase-out of all chlorine chemicals,
including those used to manufacture pharmaceuticals and sanitize
water supplies.  Bahouth echoes the contemporary attitude that
the environment must be conserved not for man's use, but for nature's
own sake.  In his view, the environmental challenge &quot;is to
expand our collective sense of care and return responsibility
towards not just our extended human family, but to other living
species as well.&quot;  The stated goals of the Foundation are
&quot;preventing damage to the natural system&quot; and &quot;supporting
innovative institutions committed to protecting the  Earth's natural
systems and ensuring a sustainable and better world for all its
inhabitants.&quot;
<P>
Turner Foundation grants are targetted to the issues
of energy, protection of forests and other habitat, population,
and water and toxics.  &quot;Nearly 300 groups representing a
broad range of approaches received grants from the Turner Foundation
in 1995,&quot; says Bahouth.  &quot;Most are small groups of citizens
who are concerned about their communities and want to make them
better places to live.&quot;  The Foundation has made several
environment-related grants to leftist organizations like the Institute
for Policy Studies and Fairness &amp; Accuracy in Reporting (FAIR).
<P>
Favoring &quot;sound population policies,&quot;
the foundation has funded a campaign aimed at teen pregnancy in
Georgia, where it is headquartered.  According to Bahouth, &quot;The
vision of this work is, 'All teens are entitled to a healthy adolescence,
free of unwanted and unplanned pregnancies, and characterized
by hope and opportunity for a productive future.&quot;  In 1995
population grants recipients included Concerned Women for Family
Planning, Georgia Population Initiative, Population Action International,
Catholics for a Free Choice, The Center for Reproductive Law &amp;
Policy, Planned Parenthood Federation of America, Families First,
and the  League of Women Voters Population Coalition.  The Turner
Foundation does not publish the amounts of its grants.  Other
1995 grant recipients were the following:
<P>
Alliance for the Wild Rockies, American Rivers,
American Wildlands, Biodiversity Legal Foundation, Center for
International Environmental Law, Earth Island Institute, Environmental
Media Services, Environmental Working Group, Friends of the Earth,
 Government Accountability Project, Kentucky Hemp Growers Cooperative
Museum &amp; Library, Land Trust Alliance, Mineral Policy Center,
Native Forest Council, Oregon Natural Resource Council, Ozone
Action, Pacific Rivers Council, Rainforest Action Network, Rocky
Mountain Institute, Safe Energy Communication Council, Southern
Environmental Law Center, Union of Concerned Citizens Wildlands
Project, Worldwatch Institute<BR>
<P>
<a name="piper">
<h4>SHE WHO PAYS THE PIPER 
CALLS THE TUNE</h4>
<P>
As grantmakers focus their giving on 
particular issues and policy strategies 
they have little by little begun to direct the environmental
advocacy agenda.  &quot;The foundations want to get something
for their money,&quot; charges Jeff St. Clair, editor of Wild
Forest Review.  &quot;They're out for control,&quot; he told the
Newhouse News Service, &quot;They want to control the policy and
political agenda of the environmental movement.&quot;  
<P>
During the 1980s, the Kendall Foundation  pressured
the largest environmental advocacy organizations into coordinating
their efforts through the so-called &quot;Group of 10&quot; meetings
of the major environmental groups.  Today the Environmental Grantmakers
Association operates from Rockefeller Family Fund offices.  &quot;As
often the sole source of funds for broad public outreach, grantmaking
becomes the focal point for inter-organizational cooperation,&quot;
the Pew Charitable Trusts' Joshua Reichert has explained. 
<P>
Pew is one of the most active foundations trying
to manage environmental advocacy (for more on Pew see &quot;Buying
Press Coverage: How Pew's Civic Journalism Project Put Newspapers,
Radio and Television Stations On the Payroll,&quot; Foundation
Watch vol.I, no.7).  For instance, in 1992 Pew and the W. Alton
Jones Foundation created Americans for the Ancient Forests, to
campaign against logging on public lands in the Pacific Northwest.
Pew also tried to organize a national campaign to pressure the
U.S. Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management to change forest
land management practices.  In 1993 it set aside $12 million to
create Earth Force, an environmental activist organization for
kids _ a sort of environmental Boy Scouts.  Earth Force was created
without consulting groups like the National Wildlife Federation
that already had extensive programs for children.
<P>
In 1991, Pew joined with the Rockefeller Foundation
and the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation to provide
$20 million to create the Energy Foundation, which promotes local
and regional regulatory policies on energy conservation and use
of low-energy-use technologies.  By pooling their resources, the
three foundations have been able to ensure that funding in this
area is focused on a single policy agenda.  The three foundations
have committed to fund the Energy Foundation for at least a decade.
 In 1993 the Energy Foundation made grants to the Environmental
Defense Fund of Texas ($500,000), Center for Neighborhood Technology
($150,000), 1,000 Friends of Oregon ($237,000), and Environmental
Action Foundation ($14,000). Environmental groups complain that
foundations are &quot;the tail wagging the dog.&quot;  Some charge
that Pew interfered with their attempt to prevent reform of the
Endangered Species Act by cutting off funds meant for the Endangered
Species Coalition and funding the Environmental Information Center
instead.  The Coalition's head, former Congressman Jim Jontz,
claims Pew forced him and the Coalition out of the campaign to
&quot;protect&quot; the Endangered Species Act. 
<P>
Pew executive director Rebecca Rimel acknowledges
the fear that foundations have their own priorities.  She told
The Chronicle of Philanthropy, &quot;Because by nature we are
insulated institutions, it's very hard for us to get candid and
direct feedback from the field.  So it's very easy for us to maybe
choose the wrong issue or go down the wrong road strategically.&quot;
Yet even though environmental groups gripe about foundation direction,
grantmakers report that they are overwhelmed with proposals at
the slightest indication  that they may have funds available for
particular projects.  Grassroots activist Sam Hitt explained the
paradox to High Country News: &quot;When Pew steps in, it's like
a death star in the solar system.  They set up their own gravitational
field and everyone begins to revolve around them.  I've watched
activists go through this dance of making themselves look fundable
to Pew by altering their priorities to meet Pew's goals.  I've
had it with those guys.&quot;<BR>
<P>
<P>
<a name="editor">
