one, number one <I>Foundation Watch</I> _ BRAVO! (&quot;PBS's
National Issues Convention and the Charles F. Kettering Foundation:
The Power of Money in Politics&quot;).
<P>
Thank you for the extra copies. They
are literally being snatched out of my hands. Carry on the great
work!
<P>
I have already subscribed to your Center's
monthly newsletters and look forward to receiving all of them.
<P>
Elizabeth Russinoff
<P>
Farmington Hills, MI
<P>
Re: Vol. I, no.4 article on Opera.
[&quot;Why did a reclusive widow give the Washington Opera eighteen
million dollars?&quot; <I>Culture Watch</I>] &quot;The example
of the Washington Opera has given the lie to NEA lobbyists who
claim cutting federal funding of the arts will undermine the survival
of art itself.&quot; 
<P>
Seems an odd place to find anti-NEA
sentiments. 
<P>
There is no question that the very
modest support USA has given to support of the Arts through NEA
has contributed to a growth in the arts especially dance and perhaps
Opera too etc. 
<P>
The pittance given has never been the
main support of any organization, in an era of high crime it seems
crazy to cut back on arts support.
<P>
One toilet didn't kill defense. Does
a bad grant kill the NEA?
<P>
Why not support the arts?  It beats
welfare for the defense contractors.
<P>
Mary H.D. Swift
<P>
Managing Editor
<P>
<I>The Washington Review</I>
<P>
Washington, DC
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<P>
EDITOR'S NOTE
<P>
<i>The
September-October issue of Foundation News and Commentary contains
an item about the Rockefeller Foundation's response to our request
for interviews which should interest readers of Foundation Watch.
[&quot;The Rockefeller Foundation: The Big Money Behind Multiculturalism,&quot;
vol. I, no. 4].</I>
<P>
<I> Denise Gray-Felder, director of
communications for the Rockefeller Foundation told the house organ
of the Council on Foundations that she had asked &quot;people&quot;
who had heard of our publication whether to provide interviews
with foundation president Peter C. Goldmark, Jr. and arts and
humanities program director Alberta Arthurs. They &quot;agreed
with the foundation's decision to refuse to be interviewed.&quot;</I>
<P>
<I>Gray-Felder, who told Foundation
News that she found our article &quot;bizarre&quot; and &quot;very
inaccurate,&quot; defended her decision not to present Rockefeller's
point of view: &quot;I have never done that in my 20-year public
relations career. It was a hard decision to make; it turned out
to be the right decision for us.&quot;</I>
<P>
<I>Gray-Felder and Foundation News
failed to note that we interviewed Dr. John Robert Evans, former
Chairman of the Board of the Rockefeller Foundation; Daniel P.
Garcia, a foundation trustee; and a number of other board members
who asked to remain anonymous. Not one of our interview subjects
has noted any inaccuracies in the story.</I>
<P>
<I> As for what Grey-Felder called bizarre,
we can only note that our account was based on published listings
in the Foundation's annual report.</I>
<P>
<I>The Rockefeller Foundation has given
grants to the late &quot;Tongues Untied&quot; filmmaker Marlon
Riggs; New York's Franklin Furnace, venue  for a pornographic
event by &quot;Scarlet O;&quot; Intermedia Arts in Minneapolis,
which hosted Ron Athey's HIV-positive slicing and dicing torture
performance; and Santa Monica's Highways, where Athey also performed
as well as &quot;NEA Four&quot; strippers Tim Miller and Karen
Finley, as well as another peformance artist describing &quot;sex
with Newt's mom.&quot;</I>
<P>
<I>We agree with Gray-Felder that such
organizations are bizarre. Even more bizarre has been the decision
of the Rockefeller Foundation to fund them.</I>
<P>
<BR>
