<TITLE>September 1996 -- Organization Trends</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar"
 border="0" align="left" ismap></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ot.gif">
</center>

<P>
<a name="evil">
<center><font  size=+2><b>Hear No Evil, See No Evil:</b></font>
<p>
<font  size=+2><b>The Campaign for Human Development</b></font>
<p>
<font  size=+1><i>Poverty Program Refuses to Mend its Ways</i></font></center>
<br>
<font  size=+1><b>CONTENTS</b></font>
<ul>
<li><a href="#evil">Hear No Evil, See No Evil</a><ul><li><a href="#jedi">JEDI Women</a><li><a href="#9to5">Working 9 to 5</a><li><a href="#floc">FLOC:  The Road To Beijing</a><li><a href="#poverty">Escaping Poverty</a><li><a href="#oppo">Opposition To Defense Spending</a><li><a href="#acorn">ACORN:  Still Going Strong</a><li><a href="#sr">Senior Citizens Threaten War</a></ul>
<li><a href="#bn"><b>Briefly</b> Noted</a>
<li><a href="#ot">About Organization Trends</a>
</ul>
<font  size=-1><i>The author, Ann Marie Temple, was a Summer Fellow at CRC.</i></font>
<br>
<font  size=+2><b>E</b></font>very year, on the Sunday before Thanksgiving, parish 
priests are told to collect money for the Campaign for Human 
Development (CHD).  The Campaign is the anti-poverty program of the U.S. Catholic 
Conference, and it collects $13 million annually from parishes across the 
country. Since its founding in 1970, CHD has raised more than $250 million.  
Grant recipients must meet several criteria:  Funded projects must benefit 
poverty groups by addressing &quot;basic causes of poverty&quot; and must &quot;effect 
institutional change&quot;; projects must &quot;contribute to 
a more integrated and mutually understanding society&quot;; &quot;members of the 
poverty group must have a dominant voice in the project&quot;; and finally, &quot;CHD 
funded projects must conform to the moral teachings of the Catholic Church.&quot; 
(CHD 1994-95 Annual Report)      
<p>Despite these reassuring criteria, it might surprise the average Catholic 
to see what sort of organizations his CHD donations are funding.  While 
specifically funded projects may be innocuous enough, some recipient groups are 
fighting against the &quot;moral teachings of the Catholic Church.&quot;  Organizations 
receiving thousands of dollars from the Campaign for Human Development 
officially cooperate with groups like the National Organization for Women, Planned 
Parenthood, and the Feminist Majority Foundation, among others.  These 
groups advocate abortion, gay and lesbian activism, and other causes condemned by 
the Catholic Church.  Other CHD-funded groups focus on politically liberal 
issues such as gun control, cuts in defense spending, increases in welfare 
programs, and socialized medicine.  While there is no Catholic position on these issues, it 
is doubtful that every parishioner donating money to the Campaign for Human 
Development intends his contribution to support these causes.
<P>
<a name="jedi">
<B>JEDI Women</B>
<br>
One of the most troubling things about CHD has been its persistent habit 
of funding organizations closely associated with and in some cases directly 
supportive of  the pro-abortion movement.  Despite the repeated revelation 
of these incidents, by the Capital Research Center and others, the practice 
continues.
<P>Justice, Economic Dignity and Independence for Women of Salt Lake 
City (JEDI Women) received a CHD grant of $20,000 in 1995.  In April 1996, 
JEDI Women officially endorsed the National Organization for Women's &quot;Fight 
the Right&quot; March in San Francisco, marching alongside such groups as: 
Catholics for a Free Choice; D.C. Coalition of Black Lesbians, Gay Men and Bisexuals, Inc.; Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund; National Abortion &amp; Reproductive Rights Action League (NARAL); 
Feminist Majority Foundation; Planned Parenthood Federation of America; and 
Zero Population Growth.  According to NOW, the purpose of the march was to 
show that &quot;the majority of people denounce 
the divisive hate-mongering of the right-wing; and will  with our time, money 
and votes  actively support affirmative action; economic justice; abortion 
rights and reproductive freedom; civil rights for people of color; lesbian, gay and 
bisexual rights and efforts to end violence 
against women.&quot;

<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<pre>
		One of the most troubling things about CHD has been its 
		persistent habit of funding organizations closely associated 
		with and in some cases directly supportive of the 
		pro-abortion movement.
</pre>
<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<p>
Speakers at the march included Gloria Steinem, Feminist Majority 
Foundation President Eleanor Smeal, and Phil Wilson, founder of the National Black 
Gay and Lesbian Leadership Forum.  Prominent signs and banners read: &quot;Fight 
the Radical Right&quot;; &quot;Spread Love:  Hug a Queer&quot;; and &quot;Get Your Rosaries Out 
of My Ovaries.&quot;
<p><i>Organization Trends</i> asked Timothy Collins, CHD's acting director, 
about CHD's support for groups participating in this march.  Collins responded 
that &quot;CHD cannot control every project we fund.&quot;  
<p>The Fight the Right March was not JEDI Women's only association 
with pro-abortion and gay rights activism.  JEDI Women is one of 17 members 
of UPNET, the Utah Progressive Network of Salt Lake City, founded in 1993.  
Other members of UPNET include: Planned Parenthood Association of Utah; 
Pro-Choice Coalition of Utah; Parents, Families, Friends of Lesbians &amp; Gays; 
Utahns for Choice/Student Coalition; and Utah NOW.  A brochure published by 
UPNET explains the purpose of the coalition:  &quot;UPNET organizations are 
committed to actualizing a vision of Utah as a 
place where all people, whatever their gender, race, national origin, veteran's 
status, affectional orientation, age, physical 
or mental ability, or religious beliefs, have the freedom to live their lives fully, 
without fear of violence, discrimination, or economic deprivation.&quot;
<p>The UPNET Education Fund holds its meetings each month at the 
Planned Parenthood Association of Utah Community Meeting Room.  
<p>JEDI Women was profiled in the Spring 1996 issue of the 
<i>Utah Progressive News</i>, the newsletter of UPNET. 
 In the same issue, an article entitled &quot;Utah Legislature Passes 
Anti-Choice Bills&quot; complains of legislation 
requiring women to receive counseling 24 hours prior to an abortion and to watch a 
video on fetal development.  The article expresses relief that a bill to ban partial 
birth abortion &quot;was watered down to the point of being ineffectual.&quot;  The issue 
also featured a report on efforts by UPNET to &quot;support the efforts of students in 
local high schools to form support clubs in which students can be open about 
their sexual identity.&quot;  The article notes 
that UPNET has &quot;played a major role in opening dialogue in Utah about gay 
youth specifically, and homosexuality, generally.&quot;
<p>The 1996 UPNET Member Organization Calendar includes: &quot;April 1: 
Utah State Liberal Appreciation Day&quot;; 
&quot;April 5: Planned Parenthood benefit&quot;; 
&quot;May 18: Pro-Choice Coalition Workshop&quot;; &quot;June 9:  Utah GAY PRIDE DAY: 
 Come Out!  Come Out!  Wherever You Are!&quot;; and &quot;June 29:  NOW 
National Conference in Las Vegas.&quot;
<p>
<a name="9to5">
<b>Working 9 to 5</b>
<br>
JEDI Women is not the only CHD grant recipient to support causes that 
do not &quot;conform to the moral teachings of the Catholic Church.&quot;  (Indeed, what 
is striking is the ease with which one finds such groups.)  9 to 5/Working 
Women, <br>
was profiled in the Campaign for Human Development 1994-95 Annual Report. 
 Ellen Bravo, national director of 9 to 5, is quoted as saying:  &quot;CHD was the 
one place you could go to get money for organizing.  That was what we 
believed we needed to be doingorganizing, reaching out to the largest sector of 
the workforce which was clearly being discriminated against and had no 
public voice . . . CHD was really there for us, and we couldn't have made it 
without them.&quot;
<p>Milwaukee 9 to 5, Inc., recently received $35,000 from CHD for its 
Wage Replacement for Family Leave Project. Sounds nice, but what else does 9 to 
5 do?  In February, Ellen Bravo, representing 9 to 5, spoke at Expo `96 
for Women's Empowerment in Washington, D.C.  The Feminist Majority 
Foundation was the primary sponsor of the Expo, and other sponsors include the 
pro-abortion political group EMILY's List, NARAL, National Abortion 
Federation, National Gay and Lesbian Task Force, National Association for Women, 
National Family Planning and Reproductive Health Association, Planned 
Parenthood Federation of America, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals 
(PETA), Women's Environment and Development Organization (WEDO), and Zero 
Population Growth.  Prominent speakers at the Expo were Eleanor Smeal of 
the Feminist Majority Foundation, Bella Abzug of WEDO, Gloria Steinem, 
founder of <i>Ms. Magazine</i>, and Patricia Ireland of NOW.  Singer Helen Reddy 
performed, &quot;I am woman, hear me roar.&quot;  The Expo was not an isolated incident 
for 9 to 5/Working Women; in April, the group joined Jedi Women in 
endorsing NOW's Fight the Right March.
<p>
<a name="floc">
<b>FLOC:  The Road to Beijing</b>
<br>
The Farm Labor Organizing Committee (FLOC) was also profiled in 
CHD's Annual Report, and FLOC President Beldamar Velasquez received the 
CHD Development of People Award in 1992.  According to 
<i>Dignidad</i>, the organization's newsletter, FLOC 
works with WEDO and Greenpeace on the steering committee for the National 
Coalition for Health and Environmental Justice, set up after a 1995 
environmental summit in Albuquerque. WEDO is known as a radical supporter of abortion 
and population control programs. WEDO invited Beatriz Maya, the FLOC 
representative at the summit, to attend the Non-Governmental Organizations Forum 
on Women, which was held in conjunction  with the U.N.'s Women's 
Conference in Beijing, China.  

<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<pre>
		An influential group of experts in Roman Catholic church law has 
		concluded that ordaining women as deacons in the church
		would be in keeping with Catholic theology and past 
		practice.  &quot;Some &quot;inroad.&quot;
</pre>
<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<p>
Maya described the forum in an article entitled 
&quot;ACTIVISM! Breaks Out in Beijing,&quot; 
explaining the negotiations over the conference's Platform for Action.  She included 
the Church in her complaints over &quot;strong conservative opposition&quot; to women 
and their work at the conference.   Maya points out that Argentinean 
women, working for &quot;the right to a safe 
abortion,&quot; are unhappy  that &quot;the Catholic 
Church had forced the government to include [Church] representatives in the 
official delegation and were backing off all promises.&quot;  She went on to assure her 
readers that in spite of these &quot;challenges,&quot; 
the Platform for Action &quot;made significant advances on . . . sexual and 
reproductive rights.&quot;<br>
<p><i>Flocista</i>, another newsletter put out by FLOC, recently hired a new 
Assistant Editor and Development Team member, Alexander Goodrum. The newsletter 
announced that Goodrum &quot;comes to FLOC from many years working for 
grassroots movements fighting for African-American justice and equality, 
international peace and justice, and equality for 
gay, transsexual and lesbian Americans.&quot;  
<p>Like FLOC, the Center for Community Advocacy (CCA) of Salinas, 
CA, was founded to work with farmworkers, and it recently received $35,000 
from CHD.  According to CCA, the group is &quot;Dedicated to improving 
farmworker housing conditions and helping farmworkers help themselves.&quot;  
CCA provides a number of access services to other organizations and boasts about 
its &quot;strong network of contacts.&quot;  
Planned Parenthood is one of the groups CCA &quot;collaborated and provided . . . 
access services to.&quot;  The author<b><i> 
</b></i>obtained this information in a ten minute 
conversation with the CCA director, and found the same information in a CCA abstract. 
 Certainly CHD grantmakers should have access to the same information.
<p>
<a name="poverty">
<b>Escaping Poverty</b>
<br>People Escaping Poverty Project (PEPP) of Fargo, ND, has 
received $60,000 from CHD in the last two years.  PEPP is a liberal organization that 
cooperates with a variety of leftist activists.  Curious readers might visit the 
PEPP web site, http://www.und.nodak.edu/org/PEPP/mission8.htm. They will find 
links to &quot;PEPP Activist pages.&quot;  One of 
the activists is &quot;Leftist Leon,&quot; whose 
home page displays four photos of Rush Limbaugh, with swastikas on his 
forehead, in various states of decay and distortion. Click on &quot;Join PEPP and 
Fight for Justice&quot; and find a detailed 
account of PEPP &quot;associates&quot; illegally 
plastering &quot;Tax the Rich&quot; signs throughout 
downtown Washington, D.C., complete with photographs.  Captions to the photos 
are revealing:  &quot;The first `hit' of the 
evening in a traditional location. . . . We were ostensibly on our way down 16th 
Street to Lafayette Park. . . ; a large contingent of aimlessly loitering and wandering 
police forced us to make other plans.&quot; Another photograph bears the 
following description:  &quot;One of the city's 
many newspaper vending boxes . . . takes a direct hit downtown.  This particular 
box dispenses every Washingtonian's favorite rightist Moonie rag, the 
<i>Washington Times</i>.&quot;
<p>According to the activists, this &quot;Tax the Rich&quot; vandalism occurred on 
the fifth anniversary of their &quot;first wheatpasting, . . . to coincide with 
actions in protest against the Persian Gulf War that were going on in DC 
during January and February 1991.&quot;
<p>Under the heading &quot;Progressive Links that inspire us,&quot;  the PEPP 
homepage gives a direct link to &quot;The 
Progressive Directory.&quot;  PEPP also provides an 
&quot;Activist Resource Page.&quot;   This invites readers to view a &quot;Calendar of 
Ann Arbor-area Progressive/Left events and meetings&quot; and &quot;Jay's Leftist and 
`Progressive' Internet Resources Directory.&quot;  The index of PEPP's &quot;Activist 
Resource Page&quot; includes &quot;Anti-War Activism&quot;; 
 &quot;Left Parties (U.S)&quot;; &quot;Lesbian / 
Gay Resources&quot;; and &quot;Marxist Writings / Socialist Revolution.&quot;  Back at the 
PEPP homepage, the heading &quot;Politics&quot; 
leads to another &quot;progressive link&quot; that 
inspires PEPP.  Clicking here, the reader will find 45 links to what they call 
&quot;inspiring&quot; organizations such as the 
Feminist Majority Foundation, conservatively incorrect, 
<i>Mother Jones</i> Magazine, The Progressive Populist, Left Links, 
and The Anarchy Organization. 
<p>PEPP is closely associated with several other groups in the 
Fargo-Moorhead area, most notably the Women's Network of the Red River Valley.  
The Women's Network leases an office from PEPP, and has been cooperating 
with PEPP since the mid-1980's.  The author<b><i> 
</b></i>spoke with Duke Schempp, Director of PEPP, who assured us that the 
groups share &quot;issues and information.&quot;  In 
a follow-up letter, Schempp included brochures and a newsletter of the 
Women's Network and wrote &quot;We are all 
working together to address a variety of issues in our community.&quot;  

<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<pre>
		A kind of genocide on the poor  an extension of the 
		`Contract on America' in its most murderous form. ... 
		Military and domestic violence have an insidious link 	
		in the fantasy of the gun as arbiter.
</pre>
<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<p>
The Network's mission statement begins, &quot;The Women's Network is a feminist, pro-choice 
organization.&quot;  The group's newsletter, <i>Whystling 
Womyn</i>, advertises &quot;feminars,&quot; and readers are invited 
to shop at the Women's Network:  &quot;A variety of items are for sale 
including `Choice' and `Uppity Women Unite' t-shirts.&quot; Another section, entitled 
&quot;Inroads,&quot; states that &quot;
<p>
<a name="oppo">
<b>Opposition to Defense Spending</b>
<br>Issues of feminism, abortion rights and gay and lesbian rights pose 
the clearest instances in which CHD-funded organizations are at odds with the 
moral teachings of the Catholic Church.  But many CHD recipients are also 
involved in politically liberal causes.  And 
Catholic donors might not support CHD if they were more familiar with these 
organizations.  Baltimore Jobs with Peace has received $55,000 from CHD in the 
last two years.  Jobs with Peace exists primarily to fight federal defense 
spending and, according to Jobs with Peace, 
&quot;continually strives to make connections between poverty and military spending.&quot; 
 Jobs with Peace led other Baltimore organizations in forming the 
Baltimore Peace Network, &quot;a long term network for action.&quot;  According to Jobs 
with Peace, &quot;In its short history, the 
Network has already tackled issues such as hand-gun control and the use of nuclear 
power to fuel space exploration vehicles.&quot;  
<p>The Baltimore Jobs with Peace newsletter describes the activities and 
accomplishments of Jobs with Peace and the Baltimore Peace Network.  It 
features articles calling for the abolition of all nuclear weapons and contrasts 
&quot;Cuts passed in the House&quot; (&quot;500 million 
cut from the Clean Water Act&quot;) with &quot;Pentagon Pork&quot; (which includes money 
for B-2 stealth bombers, military helicopters and improvements to the National 
Guard and Reserves).  A half-page of the newsletter proclaims:  &quot;Boycott French 
Products . . . Join the worldwide protests against French products until France 
reverses its decision to resume nuclear weapons testing in the South Pacific.&quot;  
<p>In an article entitled &quot;Little Guns Demand Activists' Attention, Too!,&quot; a 
Jobs with Peace board member describes the &quot;cynical pitch&quot; of the &quot;gun lobby&quot;  
which &quot;piously pleads that gun control endangers the civil rights of Americans.&quot;  
According to the newsletter, this &quot;cynical pitch . . . benefits only the arms 
manufacturers, the political right wing, and the corporate culture which spawns 
them both.&quot;  The article continues:  &quot;The 
more `respectable' pushers invoke the `constitutional right to bear arms' another inaccuracy.  But a growing army of 
right wing extremists get right down to cases.  They speak openly of a need to 
protect their homes against `government invasion,' which will destroy America's 
patriotic ideals!&quot;

<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<pre>
		Were parishioners who gave money to CHD told their 
		contributions would be going to support socialized medicine and 
		to fight the Contract with America?
</pre>
<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<p>
The article continues:  &quot;Of course, this not-so-subtle racist code implies that 
the growing ranks of the unemployed and the homeless, especially the 
minorities, will one day invade the homes of the `haves,' and must be stopped by a 
fully armed and prepared citizenry.  Blowing up an occasional Federal building 
evidently helps test that `preparedness.' But whatever the disingenuous patter 
for free access to handguns and automatic weapons, the results are indisputable: 
 blood on the streets in the economic ghettos of America  a kind of 
genocide on the poor  an extension of the `Contract on America' in its most 
murderous form. . . . Military and domestic 
violence have an insidious link in the fantasy of 
the gun as arbiter.&quot;
<p>The article concludes by referring to the &quot;gun lobby&quot; as &quot;the enemy&quot; and 
as the &quot;merchants of death, whose sales pitch is world power through fire power!&quot; 
 Aside from its fallacious and fevered rhetoric, the Jobs with Peace 
article raises the question of why the U.S. Catholic Conference is funding 
overtly political, left-wing organizations 
involved in volatile issues that have no 
connection to the causes or interests of the 
Catholic Church.  
<p>
<a name="acorn">
<b>ACORN:  Still Going Strong</b>
<br>A longtime recipient of CHD grants, the Association of Community 
Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN), claims to work for the poor by 
organizing unemployed workers and fighting for laws &quot;that require employers to hire the unemployed.&quot; In the last two years, 
CHD has given $784,000 to ACORN.  ACORN endorsed the Fight the Right March 
and sponsored the Feminist Majority Expo.  Maude Hurd, President of ACORN, 
and Marilyn Ashley, Director of Training, both spoke at the Expo.  ACORN's 
 involvement with pro-abortion, feminist groups is only the latest episode in 
a history of left-wing activism.  <i>Organization 
Trends</i> has reported on ACORN's antics in the past: coercing 
businesses into compliance by threatening legal action, pressuring financial regulators, 
picketing small businesses, and harassing public figures.  Banks are prime targets. 
 ACORN pressures them to increase set-aside loans for favored groups 
by threatening to use the federal Community Reinvestment Act against 
financial organizations that refuse to comply with its demands.  ACORN activist 
Cynthia Mason summed up the group's policy when she said:  &quot;The lesson is that . . 
. when you do an action like that, you know you have the powerand 
that's what its all about.&quot;
<p>ACORN has been fighting for a minimum wage increase, but ACORN's 
leaders have apparently ceased to believe their rhetoric.  ACORN received 
press attention earlier this year for filing 
for exemption from paying minimum wage to its own employees in California.  
As cited in an article by Richard B. Berman of the Employment Policies 
Institute, ACORN supports the minimum wage because it improves the standard of 
living of workers and &quot;employment levels increase.&quot;  However, ACORN 
doesn't want to pay minimum wage to its own workers because, according 
to ACORN's legal brief, &quot;. . . the more that ACORN must pay each individual 
outreach workereither because of minimum wage or overtime 
requirementsthe fewer outreach workers it will be able to hire.&quot;    In other words, 
ACORN continues to fight for a minimum wage increase knowing it will cause more 
unemployment.  ACORN's legal brief explains that &quot;California's minimum 
wage laws as applied to Plaintiff [ACORN] affect the quality and quantity of 
staff which Plaintiff can retain.&quot;  Is the 
Campaign for Human Development comfortable with this kind of hypocrisy?
<p>
<a name="sr">
<b>Senior Citizens Threaten War</b>
<br>Massachusetts Senior Action Council (MSAC) is another politically liberal 
organization receiving CHD funds.  MSAC's own publication exposes 
the group as radically liberal, bordering on socialist.  The back page of the 
MSAC Spring 1996 newsletter is taken up by an ad for &quot;A Forum on Consumer / 
Provider Advocacy Featuring Ralph Nader.&quot;

<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<pre>
		CHD betrays a trust in accepting money from loyal but 
		unsuspecting parishioners to use for projects that most 
		Catholics would not otherwise support.
</pre>
<hr width=50% align=center size=3>
<p>  
The Winter 1995-96 edition of the newsletter describes the MSAC Convention, 
where &quot;conventiongoers . . . resolved to advocate for a single-payer national 
health care system.&quot;  Kip Tiernan, a speaker at the convention, announced, &quot;We're 
madder than hell and we're just not going to take it any more.&quot;  The &quot;theme&quot; of 
the convention was &quot;`Defending Our Lives:  Fight the Cuts!  Rip up the 
Contract!'&quot; and posters read, &quot;`Newt!  WE 
DID NOT SIGN YOUR CONTRACT!'&quot;  MSAC President Madeline Therrien 
said, &quot;If the right wing wants war, it is war they will get.&quot;  In another article, 
MSAC Vice-President Oscar Farmer describes the proposed Republican budget as 
&quot;fascism.&quot;  
<p>MSAC is not shy about its politics.  Several Democratic state 
representatives have placed ads in the MSAC newsletter, in which many of the 
articles condemn the Republican party or Republican members of Congress.  In 
one article Kip Tiernan complains that &quot;The medical cuts being offered by the 
Republicans . . . will cost local hospitals 71,000 jobs. . . . But it will be great 
news to the privatizers [of health care].&quot;  
Proposed health care reforms are called &quot;a perverse, greedy method of 
re-distribution.&quot;  The article reveals that MSAC wants a Canadian-style health care 
system, and it lauds Hillary Clinton's early plans for universal health care.  
Defenders of CHD deny that this kind of activism is political.  Yet would they argue 
that MSAC is not political?  Were parishioners who gave money to CHD told 
their contributions would be going to support socialized medicine and to fight the 
Contract with America?
<p>A close look at CHD recipient groups paints a disturbing picture.  Catholic 
parishioners are donating millions of dollars to fringe groups that place political 
organizing above charity.  These groups are motivated not so much by a desire 
to good as they are by an unwavering faith in the welfare state.  Disconnected 
from reality, they remain wedded to the redistributionist policies of the 1960s. 
 Even worse, in far too many cases they involve themselves in causes hostile 
to Catholicism.
<p>The Campaign for Human Development is seriously negligent in 
examining the goals, leadership and activities of 
the groups receiving CHD funds.  Moreover, it is clear that CHD staff 
and directors are oblivious to economics and recent history.  Like the groups 
they bankroll, they are dedicated to a discredited collectivist vision.  For them, the 
era of big government will never end.
<p>CHD betrays a trust in accepting money from loyal but unsuspecting 
parishioners to use for projects that most Catholics would not otherwise support. 
 There is now talk that the bishops are considering reforming the Campaign.
<p>The Catholic Conference has been engaged in a protracted search for a 
new CHD executive director.  It is imperative that Catholics make known their 
displeasure with this failed program.  On Sunday, November 21, parishioners 
should drop a note to their bishop in the collection basket, and save their 
hard-earned dollars for a more worthy cause.
<p>


<hr>
<P>
<a name="bn">
<font  size=+3><b>Briefly</b> Noted</font>
<br>
The Republican Platform adopted at the party's August convention in San Diego includes a plank supporting passage of legislation to prohibit federal grantees from engaging in advocacy activities.  Last year, Congress was unable to pass such a measure -- sponsored by Republican Reps. David McIntosh (IN), Ernest Istook (OK), and Robert Ehrlich (MD).  The new Congress that takes office in January can be expected to address the issue again.
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
Rep. John Doolittle has introduced a resolution that amends the rules of the House to require witnesses at committee hearings to submit statements identifying federal grants or contracts received during the past two fiscal years.
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
More tales from the timid:  Efforts to abolish the Legal Services Corporation (LSC), long a source of funds for the radical left, suffered a serious setback on July 23 when 56 Republicans joined Democrats to defeat an attempt to cut the LSC budget by nearly 50 percent.  Instead of reducing funding, the House voted to increase spending from $141 million to $250 million.  Among the big government Republicans voting for the increase were:  Charles Canady (FL), Jon Fox (PA), Steve Gunderson (WI), Martin Hoke (OH), Bill McCollum (FL), John Porter (IL), and Curt Weldon (PA). 
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
Roger Charles, the reporter who broke the story on Admiral Jeremy Boorda's right to wear combat decorations, has been fired from his job with the <b>NATIONAL SECURITY NEWS SERVICE</b>, the left-wing agency that feeds anti-military stories to media organs like the <I>Washington Post</I> and <b>ABC News</b>.  Since Boorda's suicide, the group has reportedly experienced a backlash and lost significant funding.  The Ploughshares Fund decided not to renew a $40,000 grant to the News Service. [<I>Washington Post</I>]
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
According to a recently released General Accounting Office report, Agriculture Undersecretary Ellen Haas, formerly head of <b>PUBLIC VOICE FOR FOOD AND HEALTH POLICY</b>, frequently exceeded per diem rates on government travel expenses.  The report cites six instances were Haas stayed at five-star hotels, running up expenses well beyond what the government allows.  In addition, the report alleges that Haas hired a former Public Voice associate at an inflated salary.  The GAO report says Segal-Goodis, who was hired to run the Team Nutrition program, exaggerated her earnings and misrepresented on her application that she received a college degree from a Florida community college. [<I>Washington Post</I>]
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
<b>PRO VITA ADVISORS</b> has examined reports published by the <b>INTERFAITH CENTER ON CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY</b>, a coalition of 275 religious communities, agencies, pension funds, health care systems, and dioceses, to see what issues excite ICCR's members, over 80 percent of whom are Roman Catholic related groups.  Out of 185 shareholder resolutions, 41 dealt with tobacco.  Other issues included nuclear energy, the environment, international lending, and &quot;global corporate accountability.&quot;  &quot;The issues were varied and the resolutions imaginative,&quot; says <I>The Advisor</I>.  But &quot;one issue that wasn't mentioned this year by these religious investors was the pro-life issue.  Of course, it hasn't been mentioned in twenty years.&quot;  Contact Pro Vita Advisors:  513-298-8125. 
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
Jumping on the bandwagon:  The liberal <b>URBAN INSTITUTE</b> has established a new <b>CENTER ON NONPROFITS AND PHILANTHROPY</b>, which will function as a source of statistical information about the nonprofit sector.  According to the press release, &quot;The Center will examine the role and impact of nonprofit organizations in maintaining civil societies, enhancing civic participation, and empowering poor and underrepresented populations.&quot;  In addition, the <b>NATIONAL CENTER FOR CHARITABLE STATISTICS</b>, which moved to the Urban Institute from the <b>INDEPENDENT SECTOR</b>, plans to develop uniform reporting standards on the activities of nonprofits, as well as provide access to its databases of nonprofit statistics.
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
The <b>CENTER FOR EQUAL OPPORTUNITY</b> has released a second, expanded edition of  <I>Alternatives to Afrocentrism</I>, a volume of essays designed to help evaluate Afrocentric curricula.  Writing in the preface, CEO President and Capital Research Center National Advisory Board member Linda Chavez posits that &quot;the re-racialization of American education in the name of Afrocentrism . . . marks an impulse to put us right back where we were before [<I>Brown v. Board of Education</I>] . . . We have already tried separating children by race, and we have yet to overcome fully the legacy of decades of such segregation.&quot;  Contact CEO:  202-639-0803.
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>
Frank L. Williams, former head of the <b>AMERICAN PARKINSON DISEASE ASSOCIATION</b>, has been sentenced to 15 months in prison for embezzling more than $1 million from the charity over seven years.  The large association has raised about $4 million for the 1996 fiscal year. [<I>New York Times</I>]
<hr width=33% align=left size=3 noshade>

<p>
<a name="ot">
<font  size=+1><b>Organization</b>Trends<br></font>
<i>Capital Research Center is a non-partisan education and research organization classified by the IRS as a 501 (c) (3) public charity.</i>
