<a name="genius">
<center><h2>GLOBALLY MINDED MACARTHUR 'GENIUSES' REFLECT PAROCHIAL CONCERNS</h2>
<h3>by Martin Morse Wooster</h3></center>
<p>
In keeping with a global pattern of thinking,  the MacArthur Foundation in past years has given its genius awards to such planet-minded environmentalists as Stephen Schneider, Paul Ehrlich,  Amory Lovins, and Lester Brown -- each of whom has put international obligations to the Lonely Planet ahead of the national rights of the United States.  The 1996 laureates of the MacArthur Fellows Program fit this familiar pattern. Just as in the past, a third of the twenty-one fellows are scientists, a third are avant-garde artists, and a third are leftist activists.  As usual, conservatives, traditional artists, and entrepreneurs have been shunned.
<p>
The MacArthur Fellows Program is a relatively small part of the MacArthur Foundation's activities. MacArthur awards $142 million in annual grants but only some $7.6 million to its "geniuses."  Fellows typically receive about a quarter of a million dollars for a period of five years, with the exact amount determined by age.
<p>
Despite its relatively small budget the Fellows program generates much of MacArthur's publicity.  Because private foundations make so few grants to individuals the MacArthur Fellows program seems more exceptional than is actually the case.   It would be a routine occurrence if the MacArthur Foundation awarded five-year, $250,000 grants to Self-Help, the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, Scribe Video Center, YouthBuild U.S.A., and the Manchester Craftsmen's Guild.  But because the foundation gives grants directly to the presidents  of these organizations--Martin Eakes, Robert Greenstein,  Louis Massiah, Dorothy Stoneman, and William Strickland--the grants appear bold and unconventional, even though these recipients will almost certainly use their prize to enrich the organizations they created.
<p>
Though fifteen of the 1996 MacArthur Fellows work for organizations, there's still a veneer of rugged individualism about the program.  "Old John D. MacArthur would perhaps be horrified by some of the labor organizers and activists who have gotten his money," essayist Richard Rodriguez noted in a 1994 article in the <i>Los Angeles Times</i>.  "Yet, there remains about the MacArthur prizes a faith that is deeply Protestant, individualistic, and capitalistic.  Give the artist big money and you will create big art."  Or, as.J. Roderick  MacArthur, son of the founder of the foundation, announced in a 1979 interview in <i>Forbes</i>,"Like the Renaissance princes, we'll find Michelangelo."
<p>
But where is he? If the MacArthur Foundation has made any review of the program, it has never made them public. Henry Louis Gates, Jr., received a MacArthur Fellowship in 1981 as an untenured member of the Yale faculty and free-lancer Tina Rosenberg was awarded a  MacArthur fellowship in 1987 at age 27 to write an interesting book about Latin America. But the Gates and Rosenberg cases are unusual. They won their MacArthurs when they were young and untenured.
<p>
It is  more typical for a MacArthur recipient to be a tenured university professor.  This year, for example, nine of the Fellows are professors, and seven of these nine are full professors, who have tenure. As <i>Los Angeles Times</i> reporter Elizabeth Venant observes, the MacArthur Fellowship "has not redirected the work or lives of most winners with full-time university jobs." Most of the professors Venant interviewed used their MacArthur  windfall to finance an IRA, help pay for the college education of their children, or as a down payment on a house.  Confirming this finding, <i>The New York Times</i> reported that 1996 winner Rebecca Goldstein would use her money to pay her daughter's Harvard tuition and consolidate her debts, a boost for a family with an annual income of over $100,000 and a retirement portfolio "well into the six figures".
<p>
Four of the 1996 MacArthur Fellows are 50 or over, and seven others are between 45 and 49.  When Roy Hoopes interviewed MacArthur recipients who were 50 or over for the AARP's <i>Modern Maturity</i>, he found the MacArthurs primarily served to generate income from lecture fees and assignments.  Some of the people Hoopes interviewed regretted that they did not receive the award when they were younger and hungrier.  
<p>
When J. Roderick MacArthur was dying of cancer in 1984, he predicted that it would take a decade for the effects of the MacArthur Fellowships to be made clear.  Now that it has been 15 years since the MacArthur Fellowships were started, it is clear that the MacArthurs have made much less of a difference than most people expected when the program was launched in 1981.  A few young scholars have used their MacArthurs to produce interesting work and many older MacArthur winners have had a more comfortable retirement.  Yet in spite of the help of more than 1,000 anonymous talent scouts who have nominated Fellows (but whose names have never been disclosed to the public), the MacArthur Foundation has failed to find anyone as talented as Michelangelo.
<p>
If the MacArthur Fellows primarily reward obscure leftists, the lustre of the prizes will dim, particularly since many of the current fellows' achievements are quite arcane.  How many people eagerly await 1996 MacArthur Fellow Allan Berube's forthcoming book, <i>Shipping Out:  Gay Life and Activism on the Great Luxury Liners</i>?  The MacArthur Fellows program is, at its heart, a philanthropic enterprise that borders on farce.  The story is not tragic or heroic, but comic. It is the tale of an unclothed emperor of the charitable world, an emperor now wishing to spread its influence and prestige through the mechanism of global taxation for the United Nations.
<p>
<hr>
<p><a name="letters">
<center><h3>LETTERS TO THE EDITOR</h3></center>

Regarding Robert Huberty's recent review of <i>The Legacy of Inherited Wealth: Interviews With Heirs</i>, we would like to correct an inaccurate impression that Mr. Huberty creates about The Inheritance Project.
<p>
Much of this review is to be commended. It astutely outlines the common emotional patterns which mar the lives of the heirs featured in our collection. It is, in fact, the careful analysis contained in the first part of the review which makes the reviewer's logical leap at the end so glaring.
<p>
From among the seventeen heirs included in this book, Mr. Huberty selects three who have supported what he calls "radical causes" in their charitable giving. He takes exception to their philanthropic choices, arguing that "heirs who contribute to radical causes that prevent the accumulation of wealth overcome the conditions that leave them feeling guilty. The resulting condition leaves everyone poorer."
<p>
Mr. Huberty is certainly entitled to his opinion about what constitutes good or bad philanthropy.  However, when he equates the choices some of our subjects have made with the goals and philosophy of our organization, he makes a leap which we find both mystifying and unethical. To accuse The Inheritance Project of "discouraging heirs from becoming true philanthropists" is to seriously misrepresent us. We do not espouse any particular approach to philanthropy. We believe that the simple act of sharing one's resources has both outer value as well as inner merit, the latter perhaps known only to the heart of the giver.
<p>
In writing this book, The Inheritance Project aimed to represent as many different experiences as possible. We interviewed more than forty heirs before we published the book, and each of them described a unique set of attitudes towards wealth and toward philanthropy. Some said they give to the traditional institutions valued by their parents, some favored grassroots causes, and some were too paralyzed to think about philanthropy at all.  We neither judge nor side with any one of them.
<p>
The Inheritance Project has put together presentations on philanthropy for a wide range of groups, from the Council on Foundations to the more progressive Impact Project. More than anything, we are interested in helping heirs to untangle their confusion about their wealth so that they can more effectively use it to benefit others. If that means, in Mr. Huberty's opinion, that we are discouraging heirs from true philanthropy we can only offer our humble apologies.<p>
<font  size=-1><i>Katherine Gibson<br>
Barbara Blouin<br>
Margaret Kiersted<br>
The Inheritance Project<br>
Blacksburg, VA<br></i></font>
<p><br>
In Foundation Watch (volume 1, number 5) it is reported that the Council on Foundations is an enthusiastic supporter of affirmative action.  But if that is the case, why do men outnumber women on their board of directors when women outnumber men in the general population?
<p>
More important, why are women and men chosen from elitist circles and not from the rank-and-file they claim to represent?  Because any group that dines on "pecan chicken mousse in bouchees" is not exactly known to associate with the Big Mac crowd. Is this not an example of classism at its worst?
<p>
And by the way, what are bouchees?
<p>
<font  size=-1><i>William A. Donohue<br>
President<br>
The Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights<br>
New York, NY</i></font>
<p><br>
When I checked the URL you provided for the Pew Charitable Trust on <i>soc.org.nonprofit</i> I came up with no DNS directory. I have found Pew at <a href="http://www.pewtrusts.com">http://www.pewtrusts.com</a>. You may want to double check and update your bookmark file.<p>
<font  size=-1><i>Charles C. Saxe<br>
Chicago, IL</i></font>
</body>
