<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Frederick Stocken</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></A>
<center><h2>Culture Watch</h2></center>
<blockquote>
<font size=+1><b><i>June 1996</i></b></font>
<H2>Why did a nice young composer <br>like Frederick Stocken<br> become the British musical establishment's<br> hated heckler?</H2>
<H3>by Laurence Jarvik</H3>
<p>
<a href="#lament">Lament for Bosnia went to the top of the charts...</a><br>
<a href="#irk">In March, 1994, irked at the realization...</a><br>
<a href="#press">The press was not nice to Stocken.</a><br>
<a href="#future">What does the future hold?</a><br>
<p>
Frederick Stocken calls himself "Britain's most backward-looking composer."  Born in 1967, Organ Scholar at Cambridge University's St. Catherine's College and a graduate of Chetham's School of 
Music, the prize-winning Fellow of the Royal College of Organists is a composer of  organ works, songs, 
wood quintets, string quartets, an oratorio, and a violin concerto.  Stocken is best-known for his lush string 
composition Lament for Bosnia (Chatsworth CD, 1993).  A private commission by wealthy English arts 
patron Todd Longstaffe-Gowan, the piece was recorded by The Strings of the New Queen's Hall Orchestra 
under the direction of John Lubbock, using gut strings instead of metal to allow for a greater warmth of 
tone. The recording session took place at EMI's  Abbey Road studios made famous by The Beatles. 
<p>
Soon he was dubbed "one of the most promising talents of his generation" by Malcolm Williamson, Master of the Queen's Musick. Williamson said of Stocken's composition, "As music becomes more 
complex and unintelligible, it is refreshing to find a composer who is producing music which is clear, 
profound, free-flowing, and superbly composed."  Stocken said that he composed the Lament "not only for 
artistic reasons, but also to raise money for the victims." Stocken and his publisher had arranged for a 
portion of the sales to go directly to "Feed the Children," a British charity which has been aiding refugee 
families in the former Yugoslavia since 1992. In this effort, Stocken combined a commitment to traditional 
British romanticism in the manner of Ralph Vaughn Williams with his own personal belief in private 
charity and private support for the arts. The Evening Standard praised Stocken fulsomely, declaring,  "At 
last a young English composer has chosen to write accessible, beautiful music which is unashamedly 
passionate and melodic."  The Spectator music critic declared, "It is music which makes me believe that a 
new Sibelius or a new Elgar has been born. Try it."
<P>
<a name="lament"></a>
<CENTER><H3>Lament for Bosnia went to the top of the charts... </H3></CENTER>
on a double bill with Samuel Barber's Adagio for String Orchestra, and the set became the number one best selling CD in London's Tower Records by early 1994. Shortly 
thereafter, Stocken began work on a violin concerto, which he planned to dedicate to Margaret Thatcher.  
But there were some clouds on Stocken's horizon. Stocken had discovered composers who wrote 
hummable melodies are black-balled by the British musical establishment. He learned this lesson the hard 
way, after he was rejected by the Royal Academy of Music with the comment: "We do not use key 
signatures here at the Academy." Stocken later acidly retorted such a remark was "equivalent to being 
turned down by an art college with the comment: 'We do not use perspective here at the Slade.'"Denied 
acceptance by the official guardians of his chosen field, Stocken plotted his next move.
<P>
<a name="irk"></a>
<CENTER><H3>In March, 1994, irked at the realization...</H3></CENTER>
that the very musical competitors  who had black-balled him enjoyed substantial taxpayer subsidies through the BBC and the Arts Council for what he considered atonal "modernist plink-plonk," 
Stocken placed a classified advertisement in The Spectator. It gave his home telephone number and read: 
"THE HECKLERS: Too afraid to boo at Modern Music? Join The Hecklers and provoke change." The 
target was an April 14, 1996 performance of Sir Harrison Birtwistle's 1989 opera Gawain. Birtwistle is the 
most prominent living composer in Britain, knighted by the Queen and recipient of an estimated $350,000 
in annual support from British institutions. <p>
Stocken took on this pillar of the musical establishment directly, 
declaring his compositional efforts to be "sonic sewage." Stocken then published a manifesto in The 
Evening Standard announcing "this evening, The Hecklers will rise to their feet, a militia for melody" as 
Birtwistle's opera Gawain "squeaks and splutters to a close at the Royal Opera House."  The event, Stocken 
told Culture Watch, "was a very feeble protest." With about two dozen colleagues, he politely waited until 
the performance had ended, stood up, and booed. The small group of protesters sitting in the top balcony 
were overwhelmed by the standing ovation the opera received from the cream of British society in the 
stalls, the cheering led by no less a personage than the chairman of the British Arts Council himself, Lord 
Gowrie.
<P>
<a name="press"></a>
<CENTER><H3>The press was not nice to Stocken. </H3></CENTER>
He was damned as a "Thatcherite," called a "self-appointed cultural policeman," 
and his group labelled "a group of young fogeys" by Classical Music, which 
concluded in an editorial that "Mr. Stocken and his bunch of halitosis-ridden hoorays are not the first [to 
protest concerts]...it was very popular with the Nazis." On May 2nd The Times condemned Stocken and his 
Hecklers as "The Red Guards of Taste" and declared "Sir Harrison...is the finest modern British composer, 
some would say of all time..." Stocken's support was slight:  a column by Miranda Jackson in Classical 
Music, an elliptical comment by Prince Charles in favor of melody, an editorial in the Journal of the 
Institute of Economic Affairs, and an article in the Sydney Morning Herald pointing out that Australians 
know that Italians boo opera all the time were all he could show in his defense. Perhaps wary of a 
controversy on unfamiliar terrain, Thatcher declined to attend the upcoming premiere of her concerto and 
Stocken has removed her name. (However,  Minister for National Heritage Virginia Bottomley will attend.) 
<p>
Yet despite the establishment's disapproval, Stocken's protest has struck a chord with the music-going 
public. British concertgoers now boo modernist performances. In August, 1995 they booed Birtwistle's 
Panic when the BBC orchestra performed it at the Proms in Royal Albert Hall. Just this April, they booed a 
modernist staging of Verdi's Nabucco -- portraying the Babylonian captivity in Auschwitz -- at the Royal 
Opera House, an incident reported on the front page of The Times. Stocken did not in attend. Instead he 
was at work on a new composition, a Mass. Stocken recently converted to Roman Catholicism at the 
Brompton Oratory where his Mass will be performed. Stocken says he wishes to dedicate his music "to the 
service of the Church" and to private patrons.  
<P>
<a name="future"></a>
<CENTER><H3>What does the future hold?</H3></CENTER>
As Washington Post music critic Tim Page told Culture Watch when asked about the Birtwistle vs. Stocken debate, "If this guy just manages to stick 
around, he'll probably be one of the old fogeys himself, someday."
<P>
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
