<HEAD>
<TITLE>THE COUNCIL ON FOUNDATIONS MESSAGE TO AMERICA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><IMG ALT="Foundation Watch" src="/crc/images/hdr-fw.gif"></center>
<font size=+1><i>Foundation Watch</i></font>
<p>
<h3>June 1996</h3>

<H2>THE COUNCIL ON FOUNDATIONS<br> MESSAGE TO AMERICA</H2>
<H3>THE ERA OF LADY BOUNTIFUL IS OVER</H3>
<P>


<a href="#bread">Bread and Circuses</a><br>
<a href="#racial">The Racial Politics Of Philanthropy</a><br>
<a href="#not">Not True Believers, Just Bureaucats</a><br>
<a href="#blood">New Blood, Subtle Changes</a><br>
<a href="#rescue">Ridings To The Rescue</a><br>
<a href="#infoage">Philanthropy In The Information Age</a><br>
<a href="#council">Council And Affinity Groups Hold Strategy
<dd>Session To Fight CCRI Ballot Measure: 
<dd>Planning Session Minutes Expose Multimillion
<dd>Dollar Foundation Push This Year</a><br>
<a href="#ate">What The Council On Foundations Ate<br>
<dd>At 'A Taste Of The South'</a><br>
<a href="#lessons">Lessons From The Fall:
<dd>Foundations And The Crisis In Arts Funding
<dd>By Robert Huberty</a><br>
<a href="#letters">Letters To The Editor</a>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
Kathleen Teltsch, who covered the philanthropy beat for The New York Times from 1979 to 1994, was 
interviewed upon her retirement by a writer for Foundation News and Commentary, a publication of the 
Council on Foundations.  She told the following story about her initiation into the world of nonprofit 
organizations. <p>
	Herb West, then president of the New York Community Trust, welcomed Teltsch's new 
assignment and took her to lunch, giving Teltsch what she considered "practical, much-needed advice."  
The advice was also in the form of a story.  It concerned the experienced foundation hand who greeted a 
young executive to his first foundation job by telling him, "Welcome to the field: you'll never eat a bad 
meal or hear an honest word." <p>
	Such is the reputation of philanthropy as understood by a correspondent of the most prestigious 
American daily newspaper.  And perhaps no organization better embodies the "field" than the Council on 
Foundations, the premier organization in American philanthropy.  Headquartered in Washington, DC, the 
Council serves over 1500 grantmaking foundations in the U.S. and abroad, helping them learn from one 
another and representing their interests to Congress and the agencies of government.  The grantmakers who 
are members of the Council hold an estimated $100 billion in assets. <p>
	Last month, the Council held its annual convention in Atlanta.  It was called "Philanthropy, 
Democracy, Participation: Work in Progress" and it met from April 22nd through April 24th at the Atlanta 
Marriott Marquis hotel.  The Marriott, a John Portman-designed 1671-room behemoth whose pod-like 
glass-enclosed express elevators speed guests through a 50-story indoor atrium, is home to the city's largest 
hotel ballroom (28,826 square feet).  And it was filled to the rafters when former President Jimmy Carter 
graced the convention's opening ceremonies, speaking to what Atlanta Constitution writer Dan Hulbert 
called "deep pockets." <p>
	No shrinking violent, Carter took the opportunity to openly pitch programs, including the troubled 
"Atlanta Project" supported, Carter mentioned, by Coca-Cola, United Parcel Service, Mariott Hotels, and 
Delta Airlines, among others. Carter also plugged the more successful, religiously-inspired Habitat for 
Humanity, and the Task Force on Disease Eradication, which with help from Precision Fabrics in 
Roanoake, Virginia  has indeed helped successfully eliminate guinea worm disease. He also put in a word 
for "Erasing the Stigma of Mental Illness," a favorite cause of former First Lady Rosalyn Carter.<p>
	Carter concluded, "I hope in the next few days you will consider a few of the things I've said and 
how we, together, can go on to greater things." It was an effective fundraising speech, and received 
tumultous applause. <p>
<P>
<a name="bread"></a>
<CENTER><H3>BREAD AND CIRCUSES</H3></CENTER>
Foundation Watch was there, too, and found Teltsch's characterization of philanthropic discourse - and diet - to be entirely 
accurate.  The convention's opening ceremonies were organized by the Host Committee for the 1996 
Olympics. The food, described by Constitution writer Hulbert as "a buffet wonderland," was indeed 
plentiful and delicious.  It was organized around the theme, "A Taste of the South."  [See box on page four..]  Foundation executives were greeted by Chinese Lion Dancers and the Hotlanta Dixieland Jazz 
Band as they mingled at the bar exchanging business cards.  Once seated at dinner, they were entertained 
by a program meant for "an influential cadre of out-of-towners" and intended to "create future funding 
opportunities for Atlanta arts groups," according to the Constitution.<p>
	The evening's entertainment was predictably multicultural and politically correct.  Its deficiencies 
in taste would foreshadow the Council's vision of philanthropy, one which would unfold during the 
subsequent days' conference sessions.
<p>        Instead of high culture, Council guests were subjected to high modernism:  the Atlanta Ballet 
performed "Read My Hips," an apparent allusion to President Bush's ill-fated promise to the electorate.  
The number featured dancers clad in black leotards engaged in what appeared to be Greco-Roman 
wrestling choreographed to a techno-pop beat. 
<p>         Mercifully, the duo of Cephas and Wiggins, Piedmont blues musicians, followed for a musical 
interlude.  They did a creditable job getting the notably rythmically-challenged crowd in a festive mood.  
Unfortunately, they were followed by some dreadful local theatre groups, including the "Cotton Patch 
Gospel" which made fun of Baptists.    
<p>        A most remarkable number was then performed by South Africa's Soweto Street Beat Dance 
Company.  "Upiyane" featured male dancers in African masks and loincloths leaping to drum beats.  After 
the techno-pop of the predominantly white Atlanta Ballet, the number provoked uneasy memories of the 
Jim Crow South among some in the audience, recollecting the delight white audiences once took in 
displays of black athleticism and imagined primitivism.  That the sterotypical number was imported from 
the country to which former Council on Foundations president James Joseph had been posted as American 
Ambassador made its selection seem ironic for the capital of the "New South."
<p>        Indeed, had the program organizers not possessed impeccable liberal credentials, the race-
consciousness of the evening's entertainment might have incited more than grumbles and muttering.
<P>
<a name="racial"></a>
<CENTER><H3>THE RACIAL POLITICS OF PHILANTHROPY</H3></CENTER>
What followed over the next several days in Atlanta had a similar tone and texture.  The lectures, panel 
discussions and symposia sponsored by the Council on Foundations seemed bent on purifying the work of 
philanthropy through ever more refined racial filters.  Modern philanthropy is troubled by appearances and 
anxious to ward off misunderstandings that it does much to create.  Hence, no act of generosity is so simple 
that it may not appear to be racially patronizing.  No call for assistance so heartfelt that it may not strike 
some as arrogant.<p>
	For instance, a panel discussion "exploring issues of democracy and civil life and the elements of 
effective civic participation" followed President Carter's speech. [For more on this topic, see Foundation 
Watch vol.I, no.1, "PBS's National Issues Convention."]  This was chaired by Roger Wilkins, who keeps 
the flame of the Great Society lit from a professorial sinecure at George Mason University.  The panel 
discussants were Elaine Jones, president of the NAACP Legal Defense Fund; Raul Yzaguirre, president of 
the National Council of La Raza; Patsy Mink, a Democratic member of the House of Representatives from 
Hawaii; William Kristol, editor of  The Weekly Standard; Leslie Lenkowsky, president of the Hudson 
Institute; and gaiashkibos, a "Consultant and Technical Advisor to Tribal Governments" who is a "Member 
of the Lac Courte Oreilles Band of the Lake Superior Chippewa Indians" from Couderay, Wisconsin and 
who begged the audience not to think of Indians as rich because many tribes are entitled to many billions 
of dollars in legalized gambling revenues.
<p>        Wilkins' introduction of the panelists began with pointed remarks linking "white males" to 
conservative politics.  Of course, there are Black, Hispanic and Asian conservatives just as there are white 
male liberals.  But Wilkins was content to indulge in stereotyping, and then allowed other panelists to make 
casually disparaging remarks about the political proclivities of white males. 
<p>        The racial routine was played out in other panels at the Council on Foundations convention.  
White males were selected to represent the voice of conservatism.  They included Father Richard John 
Neuhaus, founder of the journal First Things and John Von Kannon, a vice president and treasurer of The 
Heritage Foundation. The message was clear: white male conservatives were the ruling class, reminders of 
the realm of privilege that foundations were mobilized to fight.  As such they might occasionally be on 
display, but they were excluded from the real political work of the convention. 
<p>        Nuts-and-bolts issues such as voter registration, dealing with the media, and responding to the 
"Istook Amendment," the proposal by Rep. Ernest Istook (R-OK) to prohibit advocacy by federal grantees, 
were handled in more action-oriented sessions.  Members of OMB Watch, the Advocacy Institute, the 
Center for Public Integrity and other liberal advocacy groups used these sessions to organize their forces 
and plan strategies.  This was particularly true for the pre-conference sessions of the so-called "affinity 
groups."  [See box on the California Civil Rights Initiative on page 6]. 
<p>        If the conference program had featured Dinesh D'Souza, Christina Sommers or Thomas Sowell it 
might have ignited real fireworks.  But the conference organizers preferred a dialogue of the deaf.  When 
Hudson's Leslie Lenkowsky told Mark Rosenman of the radical Union Institute that private grantmakers 
should compensate for spending cuts in federal programs, the audience responded with silence.  However, 
Rosenman's defense of the status quo was praised and his remarks were echoed by many in the audience, 
which included Rockefeller Foundation president Peter Goldmark.  [See Foundation Watch vol.1, no.5. 
"The Rockefeller Foundation: The Big Money Behind Multiculturalism" for more.]
<P>
<a name="not"></a>
<CENTER><H3>NOT TRUE BELIEVERS, JUST BUREAUCRATS</H3></CENTER>
Reflecting on his convention experience, WeeklyStandardeditor William Kristol told Foundation Watch,  
"It was in a certain way a comedy of philanthropic correctness. I was confirmed in my sense that liberalism 
was exhausted, that they're not true believers - they're just bureaucrats."
<p>        "This is good news and bad news," he added.  "They don't have much of an answer when you ask: 
'Why don't you judge by results?'  But the institutional momentum is hard to penetrate."
<p>        Heritage's John Von Kannon was struck by the way the members of the Council on Foundation's 
mispronounced the name Istook.  "They called him "Ish-took."  They pronounced the name like a Nazi war 
criminal."  However, Von Kannon says he was pleased to speak to the convention.  "I went up to 
[moderator] Judy Woodruff and said, "I want to thank you for not attaching an ideological label to The 
Heritage Foundation."  I even met a man who came up to me afterwards, saying he was delighted to find 
another conservative there."
<p>        The stultifying and politically correct nature of the Council on Foundations has been often noted.   
Dr. Marvin Olasky, author of The Tragedy of American Compassion, has published two scathing analyses 
of the Council on Foundations for Capital Research Center.  A 1985 monograph in Capital's Studies in 
Philanthropy series concluded that "Council leaders over the years have been consistently liberal, and the 
programs they have informally advanced have been consistent with that ideology."  Referring to the 
Council's fear of isolated and un-networked philanthropy by eccentric millionaires, Olasky observed, 
"There are worse things than Lone Ranger foundations - one is a nonprofit octopus." 
<p>        Eight years later Olasky revisited the Council in Philanthropically Correct: The Story of the 
Council on Foundations, the fourteenth monograph in the Capital series. Attending the national conference, 
which was held in Chicago, Olasky interviewed a number of Council members and officials.  His 
conclusion became even more bleak:  "The Council on Foundations' utopian search for perfect systems 
derives from hatred of man as he is.  And this is not philanthropy at all."
<p>        And in 1995 The New Republic sent writer David Samuels to cover the Council on Foundations 
annual convention in San Francisco.  His lengthy article, The Failure of American Foundations: 
Philanthropical Correctness, recalled Olasky's descriptions.  Said Samuels, "To wander the halls of the 
council-sponsored conference in San Francisco is to see the cartoon pages of William Bennett and Dinesh 
D'Souza brought spectacularly to life...A startling shift in foundation funding has occurred, away from 
research and toward the support of advocacy groups and the kinds of social service programs best 
accomplished by government and private charity."  In other words, the Council on Foundations was a Pied 
Piper leading philanthropists away from philanthropy.  
<P>
<a name="blood"></a>
<CENTER><H3>NEW BLOOD, SUBTLE CHANGES</H3></CENTER>
Samuels' essay was indicative of the new critical attitude that the press and Congress were taking toward 
philanthropy. It was one of a number of developments which had a measurable effect on the Council on 
Foundations. 
<p>        The article had appeared just as Congress began debating the "Istook Amendment," the proposal 
to insure that government grants to nonprofit organizations did not end up indirectly subsidizing political 
activities.  That amendment, opposed by the Council on Foundations, when combined with The New 
Republic piece, and scandals surrounding the United Way and New Era Foundation,  had far-reaching 
consequences.
<p>        Veteran Council president James Joseph, a Yale-educated minister in the United Church of Christ, 
resigned in 1995 after fourteen years in office to take a Clinton appointment as ambassador to South 
Africa.  He was followed in retirement this year by Council board chair Marjorie Craig Benton, the wife of 
Benton Foundation president Charles Benton and a trustee of the leftist Bernard Van Leer Foundation of 
the Netherlands.  The Van Leer Foundation  has funded Israeli organizers of "Peace Now" demonstrations 
(as well as Israeli peace advocates who urge Jews to "forget" the Holocaust).
<p>
Those replacing Joseph and Benton seem to be politically better connected and more savvy about 
what a Republican Congress and a "triangulating" President will expect from the nonprofit sector.  Yet 
despite their mainstream credentials and careful acknowledgement of a new political climate, Skip Rhodes 
and Dorothy Ridings continue to articulate a liberal vision of philanthropy's purpose.
<p>
The incoming chairman of the Council on Foundations board was born and raised in Berkeley, 
California. Rhodes is a graduate of the University of California, Berkeley.  He joined Chevron in 1959 and 
has served in a number of positions, including marketing, antitrust litigation, business planning, 
government affairs, and public affairs.  Since 1986 he has been manager of Chevron's $45 million annual 
corporate contributions program.  (It is rated 4.88 out of a possible 8 - a "gentleman's C" - by Austin Fulk 
in the most recent edition of Capital's annual directory, Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy.) 
<p>         Rhodes told Foundation Watch that Chevron maintains an affirmative action program, a smoke-
free workplace, a recycling program, and actively participates in the Ms. Foundation's annual "Take Your 
Daughter To Work Day."  He added that the company was "considering" adding a "Take Your Son To 
Work Day" but had not considered a co-educational experience.
<p>        Rhodes argues that his chairmanship of the Council on Foundations "shows the inclusiveness plus 
the plurality of the membership."  He was on the board of directors only three years before being elected to 
the chairmanship this year. Rhodes took the job "because it was an opportunity to help the sector and to 
help my company."  Mixing with many foundation officials enables Rhodes to "network" and to "learn 
how others do it."  He says the activity of "sharing best practices" is a "win-win situation."  It will "expand 
my education."  
<p>        Rhodes told Foundation Watch that he hopes to rebut the anti-corporate feeling of some 
foundation officers, and he expressed pleasure that President Carter in his address had praised American 
business for its philanthropy.  Carter had applauded DuPont, which provided special filters at no cost to 
eliminate water-borne parasites such as the guinea worm in the Third World. The Chevron executive noted 
that as the first corporate officer in a decade to head the Council, he represented a minority group - 
corporate America - which accounted for only ten or twelve percent of its membership. He said he is 
grateful for the opportunity, but did not know if fears of Congressional action and the controversy over 
politically correct philanthropy were a factor in his selection.
<P>
<a name="rescue"></a>
<CENTER><H3>RIDINGS TO THE RESCUE</H3></CENTER>
Replacing James Joseph as president on February 5th was Dorothy S. Ridings, the editor of  Knight-
Ridder's Bradenton [FL] Herald.  Born in Charleston, West Virginia in 1939, Ridings is married to a 
businessman, Donald J. Ridings, and is the mother of two.  She earned journalism degrees from 
Northwestern's Medill School of Journalism and the University of North Carolina.  Ridings has been 
affiliated either as a board member or consultant with four major foundations - the Ford, Benton, Mary 
Reynolds Babcock, and John S. and James L. Knight Foundations.  
<p>        Most importantly, Ridings was president of the League of Women Voters and chair of its 
501(c)(3) Education Fund from 1982-86.  Proclaiming itself nonpartisan, especially when it seeks sole 
sponsorship of the presidential debates, the League spends about $5 million annually promoting liberal 
positions on policy issues under the guise of good government.  Described in 1992 as "just another liberal 
special interest group" by The Wall Street Journal, the League has opposed term limits and school choice, 
and supported gun control and regulatory mandates.  In 1994 it joined former House Speaker Thomas 
Foley in a legal challenge to a term limits measure that was approved by Washington state voters.  The 
action was a factor in Foley's defeat.
<p>        Ridings has promised to make the Council more open and accountable.  Her conference keynote 
address urged grantmakers to be more forthright about their activities and more accessible to the press.  
Why has she made this her goal?
<p>        "The perception was that organized philanthropy was an elitist activity," Ridings told Foundation 
Watch.  "I think a lot of grantmakers have not been media savvy and have been less than forthcoming for 
no reason other than they don't know what to do." 
<p>        The former newspaper executive confesses that some foundation leaders have not welcomed 
opportunities to explain their actions to the larger public. "There are those who say, 'That's not for us.' for 
reasons of family wealth or personal safety, or not wanting to be self-aggrandizing."  But Ridings seeks to 
reassure grantmakers that she is "not saying we all have to march to the same drummer."  Rather, she 
argues, "We ought to talk about what we do.  And the people whose work we fund ought to talk about what 
they do. We really have an obligation to help our grantees tell their story better."
<p>        Asked if a policy of openness, like Gorbachev's perestroika might not bring with it the risk of 
public disapproval, Ridings was confident.  She told Foundation Watch, "I'm a real believer in being open 
to people. It's more risky that way but in the long run it serves you better.  We're in a public business and 
we say we operate under the public trust."
<p>        Ridings says she believes the Istook amendment is a "symptom" of the "overall climate of 
distrust" surrounding philanthropy.  She hopes the Council can "become catalysts for a more open, 
encompassing public debate" about the purposes and methods of philanthropy.  "I believe debate and 
discussion educates and challenges us," she said.  Although she has a "quibble" whether her attraction to 
argument comes from a Southern sensibility, Ridings asserts that, unlike Yankees, Southerners have "never 
been very secretive" and have been "open about prejudices."  Some of this she attributes to a "strong caring 
for other people."
<p>        However, it is in her definition of caring for others that Ridings discloses the attitudes that made 
her palatable to those who named her Council on Foundations president.  Ridings takes strong exception to 
those who would limit charitable contributions to direct services to the needy, and she makes a strong case 
for the importance of advocacy activities.  "One of the reasons we have public charities is to advocate on 
behalf of the powerless," she told Foundation Watch.  "Charity is not just providing services.  A very 
important part is advocating on the part of those for whom you are providing the services."
<p>        "This is not a Lady Bountiful era of charity.  It is not food baskets and blanket distribution.  It is 
not just one thing.  You ought to be able to go down to the city council and say there: 'Charity cannot fill in 
all the gaps.'"
<P>
<a name="infoage"></a>
<CENTER><H3>PHILANTHROPY IN THE INFORMATION AGE</H3></CENTER>
A highlight of the conference was the presentation of the Wilmer Shields Rich Awards for Excellence in 
Communications.  At this grand ceremony in the grand ballroom, the Council on Foundations awarded 
prizes for best annual reports and newsletters, special reports and magazines, public information 
campaigns, published guidelines and World Wide Web homepages.  So that all might have some share of 
glory, awards were made in varying categories: for community foundations, corporate grantmakers, family 
foundations, and private foundations.  Similarly, the size of the foundation was acknowledged under $15 
million, over $15 million, over $25 million as well as the member's purpose public grantmaker or 
operating nonprofit.  
<p>        A beautiful brochure listed Gold, Silver, and Bronze award recipients.  All told, there were more 
than one hundred awards distributed for what were essentially achievements in public relations.
<p>        Each year the Council on Foundations also bestows the Robert W. Scrivner Award on a 
grantmaker "making a critical difference in a creative way"  and its Distinguished Grantmaker Award "to 
honor an individual whose long service and long-term commitment have helped elevate standards in the 
field."
<p>        Oddly, the Council has no award for the most cost-effective grants program that has delivered 
lives from welfare dependency, helped substance abusers overcome their addictions, placed abandoned 
children in loving homes, helped the handicapped, or found cures for sickness.  In other words, awards for 
actually doing good.
<p>        Ridings hesitated when Foundation Watch asked her if the Council might not institute awards of 
this sort.  "Maybe we ought to take a broader look at providing services," she said.  "But looking at awards 
programs, I'm not high on adding up more awards."  
<p>        When asked why the annual convention did not place as much emphasis on serving people 
directly as on formulating strategies for advocacy, Ridings responded, "The members make the program." 
<p>        The Council on Foundations does not need more public relations awards, nor does it require more 
rhetorical promises of "openness" or "accountability." Philanthropy's problems are not public relations 
problems, they are real ones.
<p>        What the Council needs to do is to reaffirm the centrality of service to the mission of 
philanthropy.  It ought to recognize what Bradley Foundation President Michael Joyce has called "a deep 
sense of disappointment, dismay, even shame, at the spectacle of the once-proud, optimistic, and 
forward-looking American charitable sector suddenly going AWOL at the precise moment the American 
public had turned to it with high expectations and hopes."
<p>        Unfortunately, Dorothy Ridings' declaration that "this is not a Lady Bountiful era of charity" gives 
little solace to those who were looking to her for a new era of leadership at the Council on Foundations.
<p>        Perhaps she and Skip Rhodes might reconsider their priorities  -- and put delivery of charitable 
services to the truly needy and the strengthening of traditional charitable institutions such as churches, 
orphanages, hospitals, and asylums at the top of their list.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<P>
<a name="council"></a>
<center><h3>COUNCIL AND AFFINITY GROUPS HOLD STRATEGY <br>SESSION TO FIGHT CCRI BALLOT 
MEASURE: <br>PLANNING SESSION MINUTES EXPOSE MULTIMILLION<br> DOLLAR FOUNDATION 
PUSH THIS  YEAR</center></h3>
<p>        Among the strategy sessions at the Council on Foundations event in Atlanta was one on fighting 
affirmative action, specifically the California Civil Rights Initiative scheduled for the November ballot.  
<p>        A copy of the minutes of the "joint affinity group meeting" on April 21st has been obtained by 
Foundation Watch. Called "Affirmative Action: What's at Stake," the action-oriented session was 
sponsored by Asian Americans/Pacific Islanders in Philanthropy; the Association of Black Foundation 
Executives; Hispanics in Philanthropy; the National Network of Grantmakers; Woman & Philanthropy, 
Women's Funding Network; the Working Group on Funding Lesbian and Gay Issues and the Council on 
Foundations,   "in cooperation with" the Council on Foundations and the Committee on Inclusiveness.<p>
<DD>    Some verbatim excerpts follow: 
<p>"This is an example of collaboration at its best, the mother of all collaborations,"stated Dot 
Ridings, the new president of the Council on Foundations, welcoming a large audience to an historic 
collaborative meeting of eight affinity groups in philanthropy.
<p>"I am a beneficiary of Affirmative Action, in spirit if not in letter. I am out today as a beneficiary, 
and I will do all I can not to retreat," asserted Cynthia Carey Grant, steering committee member, part of the 
statewide coalition "No on CCRI" - the so-called California Civil Rights Initiative on the ballot in 
November.
<p>        Bonnie Erbe, host of the PBS news magazine "To the Contrary" outlined the context in which the 
current attacks on affirmative action are occuring. She targed the "freelance economy" in which good jobs 
are lost, replaced by contract and contingent jobs with no benefits.
<p>        "At stake is not only affirmative action, but our collective vision for the year 2000," said [Karen] 
Narasaki [executive director of the National Asian Pacific Legal Consortium]. "Will we go back to the 
1950's or embrace the globalization of culture an economy and make it a positive force for change?"
<p>Behind the attack on affirmative action is a broad attack on women by the radical right, said Carey 
Grant. Affirmative action is only one item on their agenda. Who do they oppose? Not the extreme left, but 
moderates, centrists, even conservatives - anyone who wants to promote the welfare of the majority of the 
people.
<p>        Attacks on affirmative action always peak before elections. This is not a socially driven issues, but 
a political issue, said Barbara Arnwine, executive director of the Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights 
Under Law and head of the national consortium called Americans for a Fair Chance.
<P>
<CENTER><H3>The Strategies:</H3></CENTER>
	<B>Come together. </B>The Leadership Conference on Civil Rights is coordinating the legislative 
strategy. Asian Americans and women are important in the stuggle not to be divided (sic).
<p>        <B>Appeal to white women. </B>Surveys and focus groups indicate the more they learn about affirmative 
action, the more they support it. Equal Rights Advocates.
<p>       <B> Increase public educations.</B> Americans respond to information. Following public service ads 
conducted by Americans for a Fair Chance (a consortium of civil rights and women's rights groups in 
support of affirmative action), support among white men increased four percent; among white women it 
increased 13 percent.
<p>        <B>Hire the marketing professionals</B> - don't leave the ads to lawyers!
<p>        <B>Raise voter turnout</B>, especially minority and immigrant populations. Go to citizen classes, 
swearing in ceremonies. Support youth actions.
<p>        <B>Identify supporters in the business community.</B> Get your business allies to speak out. Citizens 
Commission on Civil Rights has documented business support on video.
<p>        <B>Support litigation</B> - court decisions are news items and thus public education tools.
<p>       <B> Show the opposition how they have benefitted.</B> Pull up our talented younger people of color; 
diversity is in the lower ranks.
<p>        <B>Use consumer power.</B> Women spend 80 cents of every consumer dollar.
<P>
<CENTER><H3>The challenge:</H3></CENTER>
	The right has coopted the dialogue. How can we get back in the discussion with a unified voice? 
Bonnie Erbe.
<p>        We  need to change the debate from who gains, who loses, to what society as a whole has gained 
and what it will lose. Karen Narasaki.
<p>        Tony Romero, program officer at the Ford Foundation agreed. Grantmakers fear that IRS 
restrictions do not allow them to defend affirmative action, he said; our staff attorneys have assured us we 
can. This a moral issue for funders he added - "we need to put our grant dollars where our mouths are."
	
<p>        According to Fall/Winter 1995 Women & Philanthropy News, an "affinity group" publication, the 
Ford foundation has awarded $1.4 million to 12 organizations to support affirmative action. Other 
foundations "actively funding affirmative action intiatives" are the Rockefeller Foundation, the Carnegie 
Croporation of New York and the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation which have granted hundreds of 
thousands of dollars to the Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights Under Law for the National Affirmative 
Action Consortium.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
