<P>
<a name="lessons"></a>
<center><h3>LESSONS FROM THE FALL:<br> FOUNDATIONS AND THE CRISIS IN ARTS FUNDING<br>
BY ROBERT HUBERTY</center></h3>
<P>
	Art Lessons: Learning for the Rise and Fall of Public Arts Funding by Alice Goldfarb Marquis 
(Basic Books, 1996, paperback, 304 pages).
<P>
	The names Mapplethorpe and Serrano ignite passionate debate on the nature and purpose of art.  
Can we know when art is obscene and blasphemous?  Should art depict obscenity and blasphemy?  If it's 
obscene and blasphemous, is it art?  Should government officials try to answer these questions before they 
spend public funds on whatever art is?  Why should government fund works of art at all?  And, the 
ultimate liberal handwringer, is refusing to fund art censorship?  
<p>        Art Lessons, Alice Goldfarb Marquis' engaging and instructive history of U.S. public funding of 
the arts, manages to put these questions into an entertaining context.  Her deft and amusing narrative 
surveys forty years of shenanigans by politicians, bureaucrats and wealthy patrons who scheme to spend 
public and private money for the creation and consumption of what is for them a valuable commodity: 
more good art.  The debate which is now culminating in bitter protest over who is responsible for squalid 
public displays began innocently enough as an exercise in high-minded liberal - and Republican - 
philanthropy.  Indeed, by carefully describing how private philanthropy made public arts funding possible, 
Marquis' study implicates it in the scandals that have led to the NEA's downfall.
<p>        Marquis does not begin her tale in 1965 when President Lyndon Johnson signed legislation 
enacting the National Endowment for the Arts.  She starts in the dark ages of the late 1950s.  A time that 
most Americans remember as happy days was for intellectuals an "age of anxiety," a time when televised 
and commercial mass culture threatened the life of the mind.  It was also a time when worried big city 
mayors watched their tax base erode as the middle class fled to their T.V. sets in suburbia.  City fathers, 
desperate for a solution to urban decay, seemed to find one in the performing arts complex, the cultural 
equivalent of the shopping center.   
<p>        Art, music and theater, they reasoned, would attract tourists and new business, lure suburbanites 
back to town at night, and give senior citizens and juvenile delinquents something useful to do.  An 
uncontroversial social benefit, art was good public relations.  So private philanthropy came to the rescue, 
working in "partnership" with public agencies to create venues for art.  John D. Rockefeller III mobilized 
Manhattan's civic elite to plan fundraising for construction of Lincoln Center; President Eisenhower signed 
legislation donating federal land for what became the Kennedy Center; and Governor Nelson Rockefeller 
established the first state arts council.  
<p>        The art moguls in Marquis' telling hardly attempted to answer the question of what art is.  Largely 
ignorant or indifferent to aesthetic questions, they were more at ease developing social and economic 
justifications for art's sake.  And they positively jumped at opportunities to work on the comparatively easy 
problems of finding money for art and developing new ways to spend it.  
<p>    Much of Art Lessons is an almost farcical recounting of the bureaucratic consequences of public 
spending on the arts.  As the NEA budget surged from $5 million to $40 million from 1969 to 1973 under 
director Nancy Hanks, a Nixon appointee, and from $100 million to $165 million from 1975 to 1979 under 
Carter appointee Livingston Biddle, there was a boom in grant administrators, categories, and applications 
(27,000 by 1982). 
<p>        Everyone wanted to get in on the act.  Big and small states jockeyed for NEA money for their arts 
councils - whose purpose is to lobby for more NEA money.  The multi-billion dollar film industry lobbied 
for NEA funding for the American Film Institute.  Dance companies multiplied on the expectation of 
continuing grants, and every congressman lobbied for his district's symphony orchestras.  
<p>        Even commercially successful art found ways to tap the federal treasury.  Since jazz ensembles 
already had ticket-paying audiences, the NEA set up and funded a nonprofit whose purpose was to fund 
presenters of jazz concerts.  The NEA even added a musical theater grants program after NEA council 
member Hal Prince, a highly successful Broadway producer, complained that composers were forced to 
move to California to write for the movies to survive.  
<p>        To be sure, arts activities rapidly increased in the 1960s and 70s.  But the Ponzi scheme of more 
groups pursuing public and private grants was sure to collapse.  NEA supporters, not Jesse Helms, 
weakened the faltering agency's capacity to identify and reward artistic excellence by demanding more 
subsidies for ever more arts groups.   
<p>        One ironic lesson of public arts funding is that it has made nonprofit arts organizations more 
financially insecure.  Marquis astutely observes that artists have been tempted by foundation philanthropy 
and by the availability of NEA grant money to overextend themselves while neglecting money-making 
opportunities.  By becoming nonprofits, the prerequisite for public funding and a mark of status for 
foundation elites, artists have forsaken the main chance - the commercial marketplace.  
<p>        Despite new technologies, artists have been led to believe that the arts cannot be self-supporting 
because they cannot achieve economies of scale.  Living hand-to-mouth on $5000 grants, they take the 
risks while administrators of foundations, arts agencies and advocacy groups reap the reward. 
<p>        Last month NEA director Jane Alexander protested Congress' $99 million appropriation and asked 
for $136 million for the next fiscal year.  These inflation-ravaged figures are a pittance.  But they represent 
the agency's continuing effort to credential arts groups, attract political patronage, and steer private funds 
toward privileged favorites.  Art Lessons does not inspire confidence that the agency can credibly fulfill 
this role.              By contrast, private philanthropy gave an estimated $9.6 billion to the arts, 
culture and humanities in 1994 (7.5 percent of all philanthropy).  A reading of Alice Marquis' study 
suggests that its credibility is also at risk.
<P>
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<P>
<a name="#letters"></a>
<CENTER><H3>LETTERS TO THE EDITOR</H3></CENTER>
I read your story on the Rockefeller Foundation [vol.1, no.4] today.  While we at the Foundation do not deliberately "avoid the limelight" as 
you charge in your story, we did choose in this isolated case, not to respond favorably to your requests for 
interviews.
<p>        Your story has confirmed my initial judgement and that of others we consulted -- that we would 
not get accurate reporting of Rockefeller Foundation positions in your publication.
<p>        Any of your readers who are interested in receiving complete and accurate descriptions of our 
current funding priorities, including our support for arts and humanities worldwide, are encouraged to call 
or write us for a copy of our 1995 annual report. We can be reached on (212) 852-8414 or by writing the 
Communications Department, Rockefeller Foundation, 420 Fifth Avenue, New York, NY 10018.<p>
Denise A. Gray-Felder<BR>
Director for Communications<BR>
The Rockefeller Foundation<BR>
New York, NY<BR>
<P>
	We would be happy to correct any specific errors you might care to point out. We did find one 
mistake in the story after it went to press. Peggy Dulany is David Rockefeller's daughter, so the family does 
have a living presence on the foundation board -- even though the name of Rockefeller has disappeared.
<P>
	I was delighted recently to discover Foundation Watch.  As a one-time denizen of the City of 
Light, the issue [vol. 1, no. 2] devoted to the decline and fall of the American Center in Paris and the 
liquidation of its jazzy, spanking new building designed by Frank Gehry was especially appalling. 
<p>         It was also a riveting read.  Your post-mortem account represents lively, no-holds-barred cultural 
reportage of a sort seldom seen in the main-stream press - particularly where international matters are 
concerned.
	Your profile on the Rockefeller Foundation [vol. 1, no. 4] was equally revealing.  The common 
thread, of course, is cutting edge philanthropy run amuck, propelled by the best and the worst of intentions.  
The excesses you have detailed (and the actions of the players you have, dare I say, outed) can be blunted 
only by rigorous investigative pieces such as these.  I look forward to more of the same.
Garry Apgar, Ph.D.<BR>
Black Rock, CT<BR>
<P>
	For a column we have just completed we have found invaluable information in your Foundation 
Watch on Public Agenda and the other foundations engaged in liberal polling and opinion-molding.<p>
Gerald Sirkin<BR>
Citizen News<BR>
New Fairfield, CT<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
