<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Foundation Watch - Rockefeller -- CRC</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center><img src="/crc/images/hdr-fw.gif" alt="Foundation Watch"></center>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">Foundation Watch<p>
</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">March 1996</font>
<P>
<h2>The Rockefeller Foundation:</h2>
<h3>Promoting Civic Virtue or Catering to the Fringe?</h3>
<a href="#rock">Rockefeller vs. Standards</a><br>
<a href="#friend">With Friends Like These...</a><br>
<a href="#ludlow">The Legacy of Ludlow</a><br>
<a href="#vocab">The Multicultural Vocabulary of the Board</a><br>
<a href="#record">The Rockefeller Record</a><br>
<a href="#hanks">Nancy Hanks: Present at the Creation</a><br>
<a href="#center">The Center and the Margins</a><br>
<a href="#power">Peter Goldmark: Power Operator</a><br>
<a href="#woman">Alberta Arthurs: A Woman of Influence</a><br>
<a href="#review">Book Review: <i>Why the Wealthy Give</i> by Francie Ostrower</a><br>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
I don't have to look at a U.S. flag in the toilet to know it's
wrong,&quot; Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich said on April
2nd. He was calling on the Phoenix Art Museum to cancel an exhibit
which featured one flag draped inside a porcelain toilet surrounded
by a jail cell and another placed on the floor to be stepped on.
<P>
Outside the museum American Legion veterans had protested the
flag abuse while inside eleven-year-old Fabian Montoya took up
the banner from the floor and folded it carefully. Museum curators
quickly replaced the flag. Director Jim Ballinger defended the
action, telling the Arizona Republic that to protect the flag
&quot;would be censorship.&quot; He declared, &quot;the artists
here are just celebrating their First Amendment rights.&quot;
<P>
Gingrich responded, &quot;When I talk about elite versus classic
American values, I think the Phoenix art exhibit is a perfect
example.&quot;
<P>
The culture that permits an arts administrator to defend flag
desecration is in great measure the culture created and funded
during the past fifteen years by the major foundations. And among
all the foundations supporting the arts, perhaps the most committed
to the goals of cultural affront and multicultural diversity --
and the anti-Americanism which goes with it -- is the Rockefeller
Foundation. It is the legacy of a living dynasty whose members
are still active in business, politics, and the arts.
<P>
Historian John Fonte wrote recently in National Review that schoolchildren
now learn &quot;that instead of one people the United States of
America consists of many diverse 'peoples.'&quot; He argues that
a multi-ethnic America has been reinterpreted through the lens
of &quot;the multiculturalist agenda [that] is shattering the
American identity.&quot; For at least a decade, that agenda has
been official policy for the Rockefeller Foundation.
<P>
<a name="rock"><b>ROCKEFELLER VS. STANDARDS</b></a>
<P>
John Frohnmayer, former chairman of the National Endowment for
the Arts during the Bush Administration, claims that since the
NEA's establishment in 1965, the Rockefeller Foundation has been
important precisely because it has &quot;sought out the under-represented
outside the mainstream in the arts.&quot; While some grantmaking
foundations fund the popular arts and others give to traditional
venues such as the opera, symphony orchestras and ballet, the
Rockefeller Foundation, says Frohnmayer, has consistently supported
the &quot;cutting edge.&quot;
<P>
Reached at his home in Bozeman, Montana, Frohnmayer told Foundation
Watch that he &quot;always considered the Rockefeller Foundation
very valuable in supporting the National Endowment for the Arts.&quot;
The Rockefeller Foundation's support is more than moral: it has
supplied millions of dollars in matching funds over the years
for NEA special projects.
<P>
The Rockefeller Foundation's early arts funding was praiseworthy,
focusing on both popular and high art and on support for performing
arts complexes such as New York City's Lincoln Center and the
American Center in Paris [see Foundation Watch vol.1, no.2 for
an account of the Center's demise]. However, according to its
own official history, presented in Senate testimony in 1990, the
Rockefeller Foundation gradually came to see its role as &quot;supporting
work which is not yet validated by time and which may not be recognized
or valued by others.&quot; This is the sort of new work, funded
on the basis of &quot;judgement of peer artists and experts&quot;
that would get the NEA in trouble in 1989.
<P>
While the Rockefeller Foundation might have gotten the NEA off
the political hook by privately funding the most controversial
works that were receiving NEA grants, instead it chose to strong-arm
the NEA to continue its support for the avant-garde.
<P>
The result: NEA funding dropped from a high of some $180 million
to its current $99.5 million appropriation. Mired in a series
of federally-funded fiascos over the works of Andres Serrano,
Robert Mapplethope, Joel-Peter Witkin, Karen Finley, Holly Hughes,
Tim Miller, John Fleck, Ron Athey, and the most recent flag incident
in Arizona, the NEA continues to confound its supporters and infuriate
its opponents by being unable to see the difference between insulting
and honoring the public's trust.
<P>
In 1990, Rockefeller Foundation president Peter Goldmark, Jr.
testified to Congress against &quot;standards&quot; for NEA-supported
art in the wake of the Mapplethorpe and Serrano controversies.
<P>
He argued, &quot;I think if it is possible to make a strong case
to put into law a standard about whether something is religiously
acceptable or whether it is obscene, no matter how harmlessly
it appears to be phrased, then I think it will likely be possible
for someone else to say we ought to have a standard that has to
do with whether the art appears to support evolution or whether
it does not, or whether it appears to be patriotic or whether
it does not. I would suggest to you, let us stay away from the
road of State involvement in content. I would argue to you that
is the only safe way in our society for the State to support the
arts.&quot;
<P>
Despite Goldmark's testimony, the NEA was reauthorized in 1990
with the stipulation that NEA awards should be made after consideration
of &quot;general standards of decency and respect for the diverse
beliefs and values of the American people.&quot; Goldmark had
failed to convince Congress, but his minions had more luck with
officials at the NEA.
<P>
<a name="friend"><b>WITH FRIENDS LIKE THESE...</b></a>
<P>
In his memoir of his life as a federal arts bureaucrat, Leaving
Town Alive (Houghton Mifflin, 1993), Frohnmayer recalls that he
suspended a NEA grant for a New York art gallery called Artist's
Space in 1989 because its material was &quot;cruder and potentially
more problematic than Mapplethorpe's photos.&quot; Frohnmayer
told Susan Wyatt, the gallery's director, that among other items
in the show, &quot;at least one photo of masturbation was potentially
obscene.&quot; Moreover, the artist, David Wojnarowicz, whose
work was prominently featured, called New York's John Cardinal
O'Connor &quot;a fat cannibal&quot; in the exhibit catalogue.
<P>
Frohnmayer decided to see the New York City exhibit for himself.
Upon arriving at the gallery, he was confronted with demonstrators,
camera crews swarmed about him, and a banner flew from a building
across the street denouncing the National Endowment for the Arts.
Wrote Frohnmayer, &quot;The scene reminded me of Tom Wolfe's descriptions
of the Bronx courthouse in Bonfire of the Vanities.&quot;
<P>
&quot;It was an extremely unpleasant situation,&quot; Frohnmayer
told Foundation Watch. &quot;I went there because I wanted to
talk to them and see the show for myself.&quot; In his book, Frohnmayer
describes a meeting with art world denizens who confronted him
over his decision to suspend the grant.
<P>
The group, he recalls, included David Wojnarowicz and leaders
of ACT UP, a group advocating radical gay rights; Andres Serrano,
whose &quot;Piss Christ&quot; photo of a crucifix in urine helped
start the NEA controversy; Martha Wilson, the director of the
Manhattan &quot;performance space&quot; called Franklin Furnace,
where Annie Sprinkle had offered her private parts for public
examination and told the audience the show was &quot;government
funded,&quot;; Nan Goldin, the curator of the exhibition; and
twenty or so others. Among those there, Frohnmayer clearly recalls,
was &quot;Alberta Arthurs, of the Rockefeller Foundation.&quot;
<P>
How did the group treat the new Chairman of the NEA in his moment
of crisis? Did they offer their services to protect the agency
from a potentially damaging political confrontation while taking
care of their &quot;cutting edge&quot; constituency with private
money? To the contrary.
<P>
Frohnmayer describes the occasion vividly: &quot;I said I had
come to listen. What I heard was a series of ad hominem attacks,
something that never before, in my pleasant existence, had been
directed at me. 'You have politicized the NEA.' 'You are a coward.'
'You have sold out the artists of this country; you should resign.'
'How do you feel about men kissing each other?' 'Why don't you
fight for removal of the language that Congress passed if you
don't like it?'
<P>
&quot;After about thirty minutes of listening to people beat up
on me, I was able to direct the conversation toward what the Arts
Endowment could do in the future,&quot; Frohnmayer wrote. &quot;I
didn't like the personal attacks, but I considered them part of
the price I had to pay to work myself out of this self-inflicted
mess. I was numb; my emotions were on hold. Only a solution mattered.&quot;
In other words, as Frohnmayer put it, &quot;We were in the process
of being had for at least the second time.&quot; And in a most
rude and unpleasant manner.
<P>
While Frohnmayer noted that Alberta Arthurs was present during
his battering, he cautioned that he thought &quot;it was not a
situation orchestrated by the Rockefeller Foundation.&quot; Yet
despite his visible discomfort, Arthurs (director of Arts and
Humanities for the Rockefeller Foundation) had said not a word
to defend Frohnmayer while he endured the torrent of verbal and
psychological abuse.
<P>
Frohnmayer confessed he was grateful to have been there in New
York for the experience. &quot;I felt the Rockefeller Foundation
was a valuable ally,&quot; he told Foundation Watch. &quot;They
had the very strong feeling that the underrepresented voices ought
to be heard.&quot; And who were the &quot;underrepresented?&quot;
Frohnmayer said it was &quot;clear&quot; that &quot;the group
way on the left was underrepresented.&quot; He estimated these
were &quot;about 20-30% of the American population.&quot;
<P>
Frohnmayer's own account to Foundation Watch presents a scene
of ideological rectification worthy of Darkness at Noon. He had
obviously strayed from the art world party line, had to endure
a self-criticism session with the relevant arts commissars and
ideological enforcers, and confess to his sins before returning
to Washington.
<P>
In retrospect, Frohnmayer concludes, &quot;They wanted to make
a point. You have to say they made their point.&quot; And he adds
that following his visit to New York, &quot;I restored the grant.&quot;
<P>
The NEA funds &quot;cutting-edge&quot; works like these, in part,
because, like a battered spouse, it has come to depend on being
tormented by grantmakers like the Rockefeller Foundation. While
the Foundation purports to defend the NEA from attacks by Congress,
it joins the &quot;arts community&quot; in abusing the NEA's processes
while denouncing the agency's integrity. The Rockefeller Foundation,
for instance, made grants to the American Civil Liberties Union
and others to sue the NEA on behalf of the artists denied grants
for offensive material: The ACLU claimed &quot;free expression&quot;
required overturning the law that the NEA respect &quot;general
standards of decency.&quot;
<P>
<a name="ludlow"><b>THE LEGACY OF LUDLOW</b></a>
<P>
No member of the Rockefeller family currently sits on the Foundation's
fifteen-member board of trustees. The family absence is a legacy
of the Foundation's role in the aftermath of the &quot;Ludlow
Massacre,&quot; which occured in 1913, the same year the Foundation
had been established. That year two women and eleven children
living in a striker's camp at the Rockefeller-dominated Colorado
Fuel and Iron company died during a raid by National Guard troops.
As Martin Morse Wooster notes in The Great Philanthropies and
the Problem of Donor Intent (Capital Research Center, 1994), &quot;the
'Ludlow Massacre' quickly became a cause celebre for the left.
Novelist Upton Sinclair picketed John D. Rockefeller's home, and
in New York City, four members of the Industrial Workers of the
World died when a bomb [intended for Rockefeller] exploded prematurely
in their apartment.&quot;
<P>
At the suggestion of Harvard president Charles Eliot, the Rockefeller
Foundation hired Mackenzie King, a Canadian politician to study
labor relations at Rockefeller-controlled businesses and improve
John D's image.
<P>
The move backfired badly. In public hearings government officials
grilled King and Rockefeller public relations advisor Ivy Lee,
and concluded that &quot;the huge philanthropic trusts, known
as foundations, appear to be a menace to the welfare of society&quot;
because they gave the wealthy a mechanism &quot;to become molders
of public thought.&quot;
<P>
Under pressure, Rockefeller transferred control over his fortune
to his children in 1916, and control over the foundation to his
son John D. Rockefeller, Jr. who, according to Wooster, made it
a principle to &quot;erect a firm wall between the Rockefeller
Foundation and the Rockefellers' personal affairs.&quot; The younger
Rockefeller also replaced his father's friends and business associates
on the Foundation board with pillars of progressivism.
<P>
Soon the reconstituted Foundation was rejecting a grant proposal
from John D. Rockefeller himself. He wanted to replace textbooks
&quot;calculated to lead astray and do harm rather than good&quot;
and he proposed to fund education with &quot;the most sane and
practical and possible views of life rather than...socialism and
some forms of Bolshevism.&quot; Rockefeller's lawyer, Starr Murphy
&quot;was aghast&quot; at this proposal and wrote &quot;it would
be extremely unwise for any donor to attempt to place limitations
on the character of the teaching which shall be given in an institution
to which he contributes.&quot; The divorce of the family from
the foundation was set.
<P>
To reconnect the Rockefeller families to the charities it had
created, the Rockefeller Brothers Fund was created in 1941 by
John D. Rockefeller 3rd, Nelson, Lawrence, Winthrop, and David.
Subsequently, the Rockefeller &quot;cousins&quot; also created
their own charitable vehicles. But the original Rockefeller Foundation
itself remained firmly in the hands of a liberal establishment
independent of the family.<a name="vocab"></a>
<P>
<b>THE MULTICULTURAL<br>
VOCABULARY OF THE BOARD</b>
<P>
Today, the legacy of an independent Rockefeller Foundation lives
on. One current board member characterizes the Rockefeller Foundation
Board of Trustees as &quot;more of a Who's Who board than a Social
Register board.&quot;
<P>
The current chair is Alice Stone Ilchman, president of Sarah Lawrence
College. Establishmentarians past and present like C. Douglas
Dillon, Cyrus Vance, and the late Dean Rusk have served, as have
media figures like pundit Bill Moyers, actor Alan Alda, and former
Times-Mirror Chairman Tom Johnson, now head of CNN, and the late
Disney exective Frank Wells. It is no surprise, then, that the
Rockefeller Foundation enjoys exceptionally good press coverage.
<P>
Moreover, as one observer remarked to Foundation Watch, &quot;When
you have two billion dollars you don't have any public relations
problems. Everybody loves you&quot;.
<P>
Perhaps for these reasons, and despite the increasing notoriety
of multiculturalism's excesses, the role of the Rockefeller Foundation
has escaped public criticism. The Rockefeller Foundation's officers
and staff have been careful to avoid the limelight and declined
to respond to Foundation Watch's requests for interviews. However,
several current and former board members freely offered their
opinions of the Foundation's cultural agenda.
<P>
The immediate former chairman of the Rockefeller Foundation board
of directors is Dr. John Robert Evans, a Canadian physician and
educator who is currently chairman of the parent company of the
Toronto Star. He told Foundation Watch that the board of trustees
had approved the Foundation's commitment to diversity and multiculturalism
because of the importance of &quot;understanding difficulties
across cultures&quot; and the need to appreciate &quot;the strength
of African American and Hispanic arts.&quot; Evans, who has served
on the Rockefeller Foundation board for fourteen years, explained
that the board's &quot;general tendency was to look at 'emerging'
areas&quot; in the arts and humanities rather than fund traditional
artistic disciplines and institutions. He said the &quot;style
of the Rockefeller Foundation&quot; was that &quot;non-expert
trustees take an interest&quot; in all areas of giving, including
the cultural realm.
<P>
Another Rockefeller director said the board was influenced greatly
in the direction of multiculturalism by a Hudson Institute report
called Workforce 2000 issued in the early 1980's. Its analysis
of demographic trends suggested that women and and minorities
held the key to America's social and economic future. However,
a source close to the Hudson Institute told Foundation Watch that
the Rockefeller Foundation &quot;took the wrong message out of
Workforce 2000. The message was that there was a problem in levels
of skills and education, not that we needed 'cultural sensitivity
training.'&quot; The source added that Hudson is currently working
on Workforce 2000 Revisited, which will make an explicit case
against multiculturalism.
<P>
Trustee Daniel P. Garcia, a vice-president of Warner Brothers
and head of the Los Angeles Airport Commission, also told Foundation
Watch that the board of directors was committed to multiculturalism
and diversity. Garcia is a former chairman of the now-defunct
Los Angeles Festival, a multi-ethnic assemblage of street fairs
and performances which banned Eurocentric theatre and dance. The
L.A. Festival was supported in part by the Rockefeller Foundation.
<P>
A Vietnam veteran and advisor to Republican Los Angeles Mayor
Richard Riordan, Garcia says he is proud that a Rockefeller Foundation
grant enabled &quot;the Bellas Artes&quot; dance troupe to come
from Mexico City to New York. Culture, he asserts, &quot;is not
a Eurocentric affair.&quot;
<P>
No art lover would deny Garcia's truism, but there is a vast difference
between a national folkloric dance ensemble and the ethnocentric
&quot;performance artists&quot; Time magazine critic Robert Hughes
has called &quot;all-purpose Barbarians.&quot;
<P>
In The Culture of Complaint (Oxford, 1993), Hughes points out
that &quot;multiculturalism means something less than genuine
curiousity about other cultural forms.&quot; It is unavoidable,
says Hughes, that, &quot;Most art made by white Americans is mediocre.
Most art made by black Americans is mediocre. Most art made by
Chinese-Americans, Japanese-Americans, and American Indians is
mediocre, too. And most art made by women is as mediocre as most
art made by men. The same applies to gays and straights and to
all the other polarities. We must therefore be extremely wary
of the sentimentality that institutional multiculturalism brings.&quot;
<P>
Yet this common-sense view from a respected art critic is out
of favor at the Rockefeller Foundation. Garcia says that Alberta
Arthurs, the Rockefeller Foundation's director of arts and humanities
for the past decade, has promoted diversity and multiculturalism
by following the &quot;general policy&quot; of the board of directors.
In 1990, Rockefeller Foundation president Peter Goldmark submitted
a copy of this policy to the U.S. Senate.
<P>
Its declared goal: &quot;The encouragement of creative artists...whose
work can advance international and intercultural work in this
country...supporting the flow of art between Third World cultures
and the United States, and increasing opportunities...for ethnic
populations in the United States.&quot;
<P>
At least one insider, however, is not impressed with Rockefeller's
policy, noting: &quot;What goes on at Rockefeller is that they
are just another group following the way culture seems to be going.
Large foundations are followers, not leaders, of what's going
on in the world.&quot;<a name="record"></a>
<P>
<b>THE ROCKEFELLER RECORD</b>
<P>
This was not always the case. The official mission of the Foundation
is to promote &quot;the well-being of mankind throughout the world.&quot;
In the sciences, for example, the Rockefeller Foundation has a
proud legacy of leadership in eliminating such infectious diseases
as yellow fever and hookworm. The Foundation also has played a
leading role in the so-called &quot;green revolution&quot; that
has spurred agricultural productivity through scientific research.
To this day, approximately fifty percent of the Foundation's budget
goes to three areas where it has been a pioneer: public health,
agriculture, and population control. Indeed, John D. Rockefeller
3rd once joked to reporters, &quot;If my parents had been exposed
to today's ideas of family planning, my brothers Win [Winthrop,
former Governor of Arkansas] and David [former chairman of the
Chase Manhattan Bank] might not have made it.&quot;
<P>
The Rockefeller Foundation is the eighth largest foundation in
the United States, with an asset portfolio worth some $2,364,552,922,
according to the most recent accounting in The Chronicle of Philanthropy.
In 1993 the Foundation distributed grants of some $93,260,988,
a little under four percent of assets.
<P>
Today the Foundation has an annual arts and humanities budget
of about $13 million, not including the Bellagio Study Center
in Italy, which provides accomodation for scholars and artists.
From 1965 to 1989 the Foundation spent about $73 million on the
arts. In 1993, the Rockefeller Foundation ranked eleventh in giving
to the arts and seventh in giving to the humanities, according
to appendices in Looking Ahead: Private Sector Giving to the Arts
and Humanities (December, 1995), a Foundation-sponsored study
for the President's Committee on the Arts and Humanities. Author
Nina Kressner Cobb's analysis reveals that Rockefeller spent about
three times as much on the arts (161 grants totalling $10,403,575)
as on the humanities ($3,405,150 for 38 grants).
<P>
But Rockefeller's influence exceeds even its large size. The reasons
are manifold. The Rockefeller name alone, despite the absence
of actual family control, associates the Foundation not only with
great wealth, but with great American cultural institutions: the
University of Chicago, New York's Museum of Modern Art and the
Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts, institutions which command
respect and due deference. Moreover, the Rockefeller family and
various Foundations have been enormously influential in the formation
of a national arts policy, a notion unheard of before the 1960s.
<P>
For example, The Rockefeller Brothers Fund, a family grantmaker,
paid for the 1965 study The Performing Arts: Problems and Prospects
(McGraw-Hill) conducted by a Rockefeller Panel chaired by John
D. Rockefeller 3rd, and staffed by Nancy Hanks, later to become
National Endowment for the Arts chairman. The establishment of
the National Endowment for the Arts can be traced directly to
that report.
<P>
Just as the Rockefellers rationalized, bureaucratized and attempted
to monopolize the oil industry, their institutional offspring
have performed the same function for a once-freewheeling arts
world. The arts grantsmakers have mangaged the growth of arts
administration by funding the creation of a corporate and government
arts bureaucracy (sometimes called &quot;public-private partnership&quot;)
to replace the once all-powerful individual impresario. For the
Rockefeller Foundation, three individuals have been key.<a name="hanks"></a>
<P>
<b>NANCY HANKS: PRESENT AT THE CREATION</b>
<P>
Nancy Hanks did not work directly for the Rockefeller Foundation.
Beginning in 1953, Hanks worked as confidential assistant to Nelson
Rockefeller, with whom she &quot;fell hopelessly in love,&quot;
according to Alice Goldfarb Marquis's account in Art Lessons:
Learning from the Rise and Fall of Public Arts Funding (Basic
Books, 1995).
<P>
Over the years, Marquis says, Hanks &quot;was so enchanted with
her lover that she mended his socks, baked his birthday cake,
and paid for lunch, when, as usual, he had no cash in his wallet.&quot;
<P>
In return, &quot;Nelson showered her with gifts, including airline
tickets, drawings and etchings by Degas and Picasso, and a $200,000
securities portfolio.&quot; Marquis says the romance ended in
1955 when a press aide to the newly-elected Governor of New York
State told Rockefeller he had to &quot;get her out of here.&quot;
In 1956 she was made a key staffer for the Special Studies Project
of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.
<P>
Although she had been &quot;shipped out,&quot; Hanks &quot;remained
a creature of the Rockefeller family,&quot; researching arts policy
for the Rockefeller report and helping to found the Arts Council
of America, still a powerful arts lobby.
<P>
Former NEA Chairman Livingston Biddle, then a top staffer for
Senator Claiborne Pell (D-RI), remembers that Nancy Hanks accompanied
John D. Rockefeller 3rd when he testified before Congress in 1965
on the NEA's behalf. Biddle recalled in his memoir, Our Government
and the Arts (American Council on the Arts, 1989), &quot;I am
sure that Nancy's fine hand was visible in the Rockefeller statement.&quot;
<P>
After the election, and backed by &quot;Rockefeller Republicans,&quot;
Hanks was appointed the second chairman of the NEA by Richard
Nixon in 1969. On her watch the NEA budget increased fifteen-fold.
In 1966 the agency had only 28 full-time staffers. By 1977 Hanks
presided over 220 employees processing over 14,000 grant applications
annually.
<P>
Then-Congressman John Brademas (D-IN), later to serve on the Rockefeller
Foundation Board and currently chairman of the President's Committee
on the Arts and Humanities, is reported by Marquis to have &quot;noted
with some envy that 'a well-placed call from Nancy triggers calls
from all over the country and these people can exercise considerable
pressure.'&quot;
<P>
When President Nixon reappointed Hanks to the NEA chairmanship
in 1973, he joked that NEA funding had increased by 900 percent.
&quot;That is why we are reappointing you here,&quot; he said.
&quot;We don't want anything else increasing by that amount.&quot;
<P>
Even when controversy erupted over the NEA's support of controversial
items like Erica Jong's feminist comic best-seller Fear of Flying
or a one word poem _ the word was &quot;LIGHGHT&quot; _ which
received a $500 grant, Hanks used her connections and political
savvy to quell opposition. While not an employee of the Rockefeller
Foundation, Hank's example has inspired the generation of cultural
bureaucrats who followed her.<a name="center"></a>
<P>
<b>THE CENTER AND THE MARGINS</b>
<P>
The Rockefeller Foundation has not always always been committed
to the cultural margins. In the 1960's, most of the grants were
for more mainstream projects. A Rockefeller Foundation time-line,
called The Rockefeller Foundation: 1913 to 1988, bears witness
to this trend.
<P>
In 1935 the Foundation established the film library at the Museum
of Modern Art in New York. In 1936 it supported travelling productions
of Shakespearean drama. In 1942 the academic discipline of American
cultural studies was established with Rockefeller funds, which
also subsidized Dumas Malone's biography of Thomas Jefferson.
<P>
In 1946, Rockefeller gave some $7.5 million for education of Southern
blacks.The Rockefeller and Ford Foundations were among the earliest
backers of Lincoln Center in New York, giving matched donations
of $2.5 million each in 1957. In 1962 the Rockefeller Foundation
gave $7 million to support publication of the Lincoln, Hamilton,
Madison, and Wilson papers. In 1963 some $85 million provided
scholarships for black university students, and summer tutoring
programs at Princeton, Dartmouth and Oberlin. In 1967 major grants
went to the Eliot Feld Ballet, the North Carolina Dance Theatre,
and the Agnes de Mille Dance Theater.
<P>
However, in 1967 major grants also went to the &quot;experimental&quot;
La Mama Theatre Company and to Joseph Papp's Public Theatre. In
1973 Rockefeller began funding &quot;women's studies&quot; programs
at Radcliffe, Sarah Lawrence, and Harvard Divinity School. In
1978 the Foundation commissioned a report on the &quot;crisis&quot;
in the humanities. In 1981 the Foundation supported minimalist
composers Philip Glass and Steve Reich.
<P>
After the NEA became operational in the late 1960's the role of
the grantmaking foundations changed. Instead of providing grants
which would allow arts institutions to flourish in an essentially
private sector economy, the foundations would now make provocative
grants to supplement the public sector support on which arts institutions
grew increasingly dependent, and to &quot;leverage&quot; public
support for the avant-garde.
<P>
Michael Straight, NEA's deputy director in the Nixon administration
indicates in his book Twigs for an Eagle's Nest (Devon Press,
1979) that &quot;A number of foundations agreed [with the primacy
of the federal role] and decided to cut back their support for
the arts.&quot; Straight, who later confessed that he was the
&quot;fifth man&quot;- turned FBI informant in the 1930s Kim Philby
Cambridge spy ring, was Nancy Hanks's troubleshooter at the NEA,
responsible for &quot;flagging&quot; controversial grants such
as one to George Plimpton's The American Literary Anthology for
a pornographic Ed Sanders story.
<P>
That was then. Private sources could and did take up the slack
in the &quot;flagged&quot; cases. But in the 1980's the Rockefeller
Foundation decided that its priority would be not only to fund
that which would not otherwise be funded, but to insist that the
Federal government fund it, too.<a name="power"></a>
<P>
<b>PETER GOLDMARK: POWER OPERATOR</b>
<P>
By the mid 1980s The Rockefeller Foundation's had strengthened
its commitment to the multicultural agenda. That agenda is shared
by two key figures, Peter Goldmark and Alberta Arthurs. Through
their control of Rockefeller's arts budget, they share responsibility
for the trend in giving which places &quot;diversity&quot; ahead
of quality in the arts.
<P>
Peter C. Goldmark, Jr., age 56, is the current president of the
Rockefeller Foundation. He was recruited to his position in 1988
by his employer, Times Mirror president Thomas Johnson who, as
a Foundation director, headed a search committee established by
the board. At the time, Goldmark was a senior vice-president of
the Eastern division of Times Mirror. (Goldmark's succeeded Richard
Lyman, a former Stanford University president who resigned under
savage criticism over his performance. Lyman's record was &quot;slouching
towards senility,&quot; wrote Waldemar Nielsen in The Golden Donors,
a major study of grantmaking foundations.)
<P>
The son of the maverick inventor of the long-playing record who
later became head of CBS Labs, Peter Goldmark Jr. is a Harvard
graduate, was once a prep-school history teacher at the Putney
School in Vermont, and worked in the War on Poverty's Office of
Economic Opportunity during the Johnson Administration. A seasoned
political veteran, he also has worked for New York Mayor John
Lindsay, New York Governor Hugh Carey, and Massachusetts Governor
Francis Sargent.
<P>
Goldmark is a former executive director of the Port Authority
of New York and New Jersey. But although praised for his personal
style as an administrator, he has a spotty record of accomplishment.
Former Governor Hugh Carey gives Goldmark a mixed review. &quot;He
didn't succeed fully at what he had hoped to do,&quot; Carey told
an interviewer for Manhattan, Inc. in 1988.
<P>
Likewise, a 1988 New York Times business section profile offered
this faint praise of Goldmark: &quot;He cannot completely hide
the boredom brought on by narrowing his sights to the challenges
facing a single company. It is obvious to those around him that
he will fit more naturally into his new role, where he can spread
his attentions to global concerns.&quot;
<P>
Goldmark's global concerns are embodied in the rhetoric of social
obligation and racial awareness. In 1968 he co-wrote the preface
for the Kerner Commission Report, which was the Johnson Administration's
response to civil unrest. His words include the famous refrain,
&quot;Our nation is moving toward two societies, one black, one
white _ separate and unequal. What white Americans have never
fully understood _ but what the Negro can never forget _ is that
white society is deeply implicated in the ghetto. White institutions
created it, white institutions maintain it, and white society
condones it.&quot;
<P>
Upon taking the Rockefeller post, Goldmark told The New York Times
that he would concentrate his attention on &quot;the underclass.&quot;
&quot;Nobody knows who they are, what they do, how they stay alive,
or why they are so totally cut off from the institutions of American
life. The only institution they come in contact with is the criminal
justice system,&quot; he told The Times' Kathleen Teltsch. &quot;The
underclass is not a topic to pursue from the library. You get
out and look for them.&quot;
<P>
Another guilty liberal? In the 1991 Rockefeller Foundation annual
report Goldmark's sense of shame assumed universal proportions:
&quot;To survive as a species of promise rather than a race of
destruction will require of us a degree of planetary cooperation
that we have barely begun to imagine. That should prompt us to
prepare soberly for the test of effectiveness. The history of
the 90's demands it.&quot;
<P>
Goldmark is well-regarded by associates and has been described
as charming and considerate. The secretaries of Rockefeller Foundation
board members know him for his Christmas gifts, which usually
are &quot;third world crafts, a pillow or embroidery,&quot; according
to one recipient.
<P>
Behind the geniality and the social conscience, however, Goldmark
runs hard. He craves power, Goldmark told Manhattan Inc. &quot;We're
very bad about talking about power in American culture. We're
probably more awkward talking about power than we are about sex.
We don't have much of a vocabulary of how to talk about power,&quot;
he said. &quot;But to exercise power...you have to believe that
every action you take is important, that every word you say is
heard.&quot;<a name="woman"></a>
<P>
<b>ALBERTA ARTHURS: A WOMAN OF INFLUENCE</b>
<P>
In the art world, power is typically exercised quietly, gloved
in velvet, behind panelled doors. As Tom Wolfe noted in The Painted
Word, the public is not invited into the decision-making process.
The results are merely announced, like weddings and funerals,
in the pages of The New York Times. This is certainly true of
Alberta Arthurs and her management style as Director of Arts and
Humanities. Immensely influential, while extremely private, Arthurs
is in the vanguard of Rockefeller's arts and humanities efforts.
She annually distributes about $13 million to some 200 successful
applicants.
<P>
While Goldmark's attentions are focused on the broadest aspects
of urban affairs, global environmental matters, and the goals
of free expression, Arthurs has made sure for over ten years that
the interests of feminism, multiculturalism, and &quot;diversity&quot;
define the Rockefeller Foundation's politicized giving in the
arts.
<P>
Among the recipients of Rockefeller Foundation largesse during
her 1994 term:
<P><ul>
<li>$25,000 to the ACLU Foundation, Inc. for the &quot;Arts Censorship
Project&quot; which paid for suing the NEA.
<P>
<li>$35,000 to the ETV Endowment of South Carolina, Inc., for pre-production
and development of a six-hour television series entitled &quot;With
God on Our Side: The Rise of the Religious Right in America.
<P>
<li>$60,000 to the Los Angeles Festival &quot;for a six-month feasibility
study of future organizational options.&quot;
<P>
<li>$75,000 to the National Black Arts Festival, Inc., Atlanta for
&quot;Celebrate Africa!&quot;
<P>
<li>$10,000 to Franklin Furnace Archive, Inc. for &quot;hiring a
consultant&quot; to &quot;implement new artistic programs.&quot;
The venue is famous for presenting Annie Sprinkle, a former prostitute
cum &quot;performance artist.&quot; The theater's basement location
was closed by the New York City Fire Department in 1990 after
complaints.
<P>
<li>$35,000 to Arthur Dong for &quot;They Called Us Lesbians.&quot;
Dong previously produced &quot;Coming Out Under Fire&quot; a film
about gays in the military.
<P>
<li>$50,000 to the National Cultural Alliance, a lobby for the NEA,
&quot;for its national campaign to expand public awareness of
the critical role of the arts and humanities in the United States.
<P>
<li>$25,000 to the National Endowment for the Arts for &quot;ART-21&quot;
a national advocacy conference
<P>
<li>$25,000 to the Nuyorican Poets Cafe in New York for &quot;a
series of developmental screenplay readings&quot; by Puerto Ricans
living in New York.
<P>
<li>$17,000 to Intermedia Arts in Minneapolis, a co-sponsor of torture
artist Ron Athey's 1994 slicing and dicing.
<P>
<li>$10,000 to 18th Street Arts Complex/Highways Performing Space,
Santa Monica, CA for &quot;development and production of &quot;The
Dodo Vaccine.&quot; Highways has hosted Ron Athey, and NEA litigants
Tim Miller and Holly Hughes. Miller is &quot;artistic director&quot;
of the venue. It was most recently in the news for presenting
a performance artist describing &quot;sex with Newt's mom,&quot;
subject of a debate on the floor of the U.S. Congress prior to
yet another NEA budget cut.
<P>
<li>$35,000 to Signifyn' Works in Berkeley, California for &quot;filmmaker
Marlon Riggs' film Black Is...Black Ain't.&quot; Riggs, a Harvard
graduate who died of AIDS in 1994, had previously produced &quot;Tongues
Untied,&quot; which created a storm of protest against its profanity
and explicit sexuality when aired on PBS in 1992. The film led
to Senate passage of a decency amendment to the Telecommunications
Act that same year, which the Supreme Court upheld against ACLU
challenges.
<P>
<li>1994-95 Rockefeller Foundation Humanities Fellowships advertised
in The Chronicle of Philanthropy include the Center for Lesbian
and Gay Studies at the Graduate School of the City University
of New York; the Susan B. Anthony Center for Women's Studies at
the University of Rochester; the Afro-American Studies Program
at Princeton University, and Claiming Social Equity and Cultural
Rights, Centro de Studios Pertorriquenos, at Hunter College, New
York.</ul>
<P>
This list is just a sampling of the venues and artists Arthur's
Rockefeller program supports. And this Foundation support for
the &quot;cutting edge&quot; can clearly be laid at Arthur's feet.
<P>
For Arthurs was already in charge of Rockefeller's arts and humanities
grants under Richard Lyman, Goldmark's predecessor. An ardent
and active feminist whom some critics call &quot;the Wicked Witch
of the West Side,&quot; she is a career academic and former college
president. A 1954 graduate of Wellesley College, Arthurs married
in 1959 and taught English at Rutgers University from 1964-73.
She earned a Bryn Mawr Ph.D. in English completing a dissertation
on landscape in the work of Jane Austen in 1972.
<P>
In 1973 Arthurs became Dean of Admissions at Radcliffe College,
then was named Dean of Undergraduate Affairs at Harvard from 1975-77,
and then served two years as president of Chatham College, a small
liberal-arts institution near Pittsburgh. She has been director
of Arts and Humanities at the Rockefeller Foundation since then.
<P>
In the late 1980's the Rockefeller Foundation began to provide
an annual one million-dollar grant to establish a new organization,
National Video Resources, Inc. Arthurs became chairman of the
board of the new enterprise. It helps to distribute &quot;independent&quot;
and &quot;avant-garde&quot; videos to libraries, schools and colleges.
To do this, it &quot;trains&quot; librarians, distributes bibliographies,
and sometimes arranges for donations.
<P>
In other words, National Video Resources subsidizes receptivity
to the type of marginal productions the Rockefeller Foundation
typically funds _ productions which would not ordinarily be included
in school curricula or library holdings without this outside &quot;incentive.&quot;
In the for-profit sector, such operations are sometimes called
bribery, kickbacks, and public relations.
<P>
No matter. Arthurs had been unafraid to advocate on behalf of
both the NEA and the NEH. Daniel Garcia, a Rockefeller Foundation
trustee, told Foundation Watch that Arthurs had &quot;given millions&quot;
over the years in matching grants to NEA projects.
<P>
Since Frohnmayer's capitulation, Arthurs has been vocal in lobbying
for the NEA. In 1993 Arthurs co-authored an op-ed piece for The
Los Angeles Times with NEA Visual Arts Policy panelist Douglas
Davis called &quot;News Flash To Washington: Americans Like the
Arts: Culture: Polls Show Strong Support For Government Leadership
and Assistance In All Fields of Creative Endeavor.&quot;
<P>
Arthurs was unrepentant, despite public outrage at the NEA's track
record of pornography, blasphemy, and horror, and despite punitive
budget cuts approved by a Democratic Congress spearheaded by the
then-Appropriations Committee Chairman, Senator Byrd (D-WV), Arthurs
argued for &quot;additional dollars&quot; for the NEA and NEH.
<P>
As recently as last year, Arthurs testified on behalf of the National
Endowment for the Humanities before the a Senate committee. Supporting
the NEH's multiculturalist promoter Sheldon Hackney, Arthurs declared
&quot;the Endowment is essential for scholarship.&quot; This was
shortly after former NEH chairmen William Bennett and Lynne Cheney
both called for the abolition of the Humanities Endowment.
<P>
If the Rockefeller Foundation faced the truth it would acknowledge
that its policies of multiculturalism and diversity have put the
future of the Arts and Humanities endowments in peril. The Rockefeller
Foundation's insistence that the federal cultural agencies maintain
these policies in the face of public outrage has sealed their
doom.
<P>
<hr><a name="review"></a>
<P>
<b><i>Why the Wealthy Give: The Culture of Elite Philanthropy </i>by Francie
Ostrower (Princeton University Press, 1995, 190 pages)
<P>
Reviewed by Robert Huberty</b>
<P>
Why the Wealthy Give won't really help a fundraiser searching
for tips _ it's too poorly written for one thing _ but it does
present some useful ideas and information to suggest why the nonprofit
sector is in its current fix.
<P>
Ostrower, a Harvard professor of sociology, interviewed 88 very
wealthy New York City-area donors in the late 1980s. She wanted
to see whether philanthropy shaped a distinctive outlook and way
of life.
<P>
The author looked for differences and tensions in her group, which
she had randomly selected from lists of big givers. Categorizing
donors by religion and ethnicity, sex and marital status, and
areas and amounts of giving, she was able to discover some interesting
variations. And by getting the donors to talk about themselves,
she learned much about what they thought they were doing.
<P>
What these unidentified donors told Ostrower has led her to conclude
that they think of themselves as a distinctive social elite, and
they regard philanthropy as an activity of their class and a symbol
of their status.
<P>
Many organize their daily lives around philanthropy: they conscientiously
serve on nonprofit boards, generously volunteer their time and
expertise, and enjoy evenings at fancy galas and receptions that
raise money for favorite charities. They recognize each other
at such events and are proud to feel an obligation to contribute
to what one called, &quot;the whole range from what's acutely
necessary to what is desirable.&quot;
<P>
However, while most Americans' philanthropy goes heavily to religion,
this figured less prominently in Ostrower's donors' priorities.
The reason may have to do with Ostrower's methodology. Surprisingly,
when Ostrower constructed her initial database she did not include
churches or synagogues.
<P>
This biases her study, since it makes her sample appear less religious
than wealthy New York City donors may be. Certainly, it resulted
in fewer interviews with wealthy Catholics, distorting the world
of philanthropy which Ostrower claims to be describing.
<P>
In other words, while Ostrower may accurately describe &quot;her&quot;
social elite, it may not be representative of New York's let alone
the nation's.
<P>
Still, the results are interesting. Ostrower's donors' favorite
causes are education (especially higher education) and cultural
institutions. Hospitals and other health-related groups follow.
Those who graduated from the most prestigious private institutions
were more likely to have made large gifts to alma mater. This
will give no comfort to those hoping for more alumni help in fighting
political correctness.
<P>
Social service agencies received more support from Jews and unmarried
women. Married women were more likely to give to culture. Public
policy, advocacy, and environmental causes had few supporters.
Jewish-federations were well-funded, no doubt because 49 donors
in the sample were Jewish, more than half.
<P>
Ostrower's sampling are typically American in many ways: they
respect individual accomplishment, distrust government power,
and believe private institutions can carry out many functions
better than government.
<P>
They value individual choice and they believe government funding
will politicize decision-making.
<P>
Unlike many Marxist academics who think such attitudes disguise
selfish class interests, Ostrower takes the donors at their word.
She thinks their sense of mission is sincere, and generally finds
their approach to giving open-minded, self-critical and pluralistic.
<P>
Yet her donors also voice attitudes which betray certain limitations
in their thinking. These prevent them from doing as much good
as they might hope to achieve. And they contribute to serious
problems in philanthropy.
<P>
One trouble with social elites is that they don't want to interact
too much with other people. It's hard to involve donors with anyone
other than their own kind.
<P>
Ostrower found that her donors did not want to give to individuals.
Rather, they contributed to prestigous organizations. Or, as she
puts it in the language peculiar to social scientists: &quot;Identifications
with organizations become a central focus of donor loyalties and
concern.&quot;
<P>
Her donors seem to exert too little muscle, not too much. Some
donors gripe that they have no influence over the nonprofit professionals
who set their groups' agendas. Others seem only to want the status
of an institutional affiliation.
<P>
But by holding themselves aloof, donors fail to exercise a power
of the purse which is uniquely theirs. Organizations cannot be
accountable to donor intentions if they don't express them.
<P>
Ostrower's sample is also not very charitable. Because building
prestige institutions is so important to them, Ostrower discovered
that her donors sharply differentiate philanthropy from charity
to individuals.
<P>
Many saw direct services to the needy _ homeless shelters, soup
kitchens, disaster relief and the like _ as an entirely separate
activity. Said one donor, &quot;I do not give money to buy clothes
and food for individuals. My tax money goes for that.&quot; What
the comment demonstrates is that the rich, like the poor, will
succumb to the culture of welfare dependency.
<P>
Finally, Ostrower's donors don't seem to have given enough serious
thought to the long-term and public policy consequences of their
wealth. They believe they have a right to choose who will receive
their money, but are ambivalent about leaving estates to their
children, and leery about philanthropy by bequest -- recognizing
that their intentions may not be honored.
<P>
Almost unanimously, they rejected a hypothetical proposal to eliminate
the tax deduction for charitable giving in order to increase government
support for welfare and cultural activities. Says Ostrower in
one of her clearer sentences, &quot;Money that goes to government
is seen as taken away, while money donated to philanthropy is
seen as money given away.&quot;
<P>
Yet large majorities agreed that government should spend more
for health care, the arts, higher education, social services,
and environmental and animal protection.
<P>
The problem is Ostrower's donors want their philanthropy to &quot;make
a difference&quot; but they can only imagine this within the context
of the familiar. They relate philanthropy to personal attachments
and social networks more than to individual charity or public
policies towards broad social goals. 
<P>
In wanting to &quot;protect&quot; their philanthropy from welfare
and other social problems that they perceive as intractable, the
rich, like all of us, may really be yielding to a despair that
nothing can be done about the poor. That's a mistake which philanthropy
can correct once donors recognize that government isn't taking
care of the big problems now, and can't be expected to do so in
the future. 
</BODY>

